This symbol represents a unary function that denotes the transpose of
the given matrix or vector
examples_normalized: $\text{A representation of the equation } \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 2 & 3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 2 \\ 1 & 3 \end{pmatrix} \text{ N.B. in this example the row oriented view of matrix construction is being assumed.}$

linalg1:determinant.name: determinant
linalg1:determinant.description:
This symbol denotes the unary function which returns the determinant
of its argument, the argument should be a square matrix.
cmp_properties: The determinant of an identity matrix is 1
linalg1:determinant.description_normalized:
This symbol denotes the unary function which returns the determinant
of its argument, the argument should be a square matrix.

linalg1:vector_selector.name: vector_selector
linalg1:vector_selector.description:
This symbol represents the function which allows individual entries to
be selected from a vector, or a matrixrow. It takes two arguments. The
first argument is the position in the vector (or matrixrow) of the
required entry, the second argument is the vector (or matrixrow) in
question. The indexing is one based, i.e. the first element is indexed by one.
examples: Representation of a specification of selection of the second element of the specific vector [3,6,9]. N.B. in this example the row oriented view of vector construction is being assumed 2 3 6 9
Representation of a specification of selection of the second element of the specific matrixrow [0,1,0]. N.B. in this example the row oriented view of matrixrow construction is being assumed 2 0 1 0
linalg1:vector_selector.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the function which allows individual entries to
be selected from a vector, or a matrixrow. It takes two arguments. The
first argument is the position in the vector (or matrixrow) of the
required entry, the second argument is the vector (or matrixrow) in
question. The indexing is one based, i.e. the first element is indexed by one.
examples_normalized: Representation of a specification of selection of the second element of the specific vector [3,6,9]. N.B. in this example the row oriented view of vector construction is being assumed 2 3 6 9
Representation of a specification of selection of the second element of the specific matrixrow [0,1,0]. N.B. in this example the row oriented view of matrixrow construction is being assumed 2 0 1 0

linalg1:matrix_selector.name: matrix_selector
linalg1:matrix_selector.description:
This symbol represents the function which allows individual entries to
be selected from a matrix. It takes three arguments, the first is the
index of the row and the second is the index of the column of the
required element, the third argument is the matrix in question. The
indexing is one based, i.e. the element in the top left hand corner is
indexed by (1,1).
examples: Representation of a specification of selection of the top left hand entry to the matrix M. 1 1
linalg1:matrix_selector.sympy_function: lambda M, i, j: M[i-1, j-1]
linalg1:matrix_selector.sympy_signature: lambda M, i, j: M[i-1, j-1]
linalg1:matrix_selector.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the function which allows individual entries to
be selected from a matrix. It takes three arguments, the first is the
index of the row and the second is the index of the column of the
required element, the third argument is the matrix in question. The
indexing is one based, i.e. the element in the top left hand corner is
indexed by (1,1).
examples_normalized: Representation of a specification of selection of the top left hand entry to the matrix M. 1 1

s_dist1:mean.name: mean
s_dist1:mean.description:
This symbol represents a unary function denoting the mean of a 
distribution. The argument is a univariate function to describe the 
distribution. That is, if f is the function describing the 
distribution. The mean is the expression integrate(x*f(x)) w.r.t. x over the
range (-infinity,infinity).
cmp_properties: mean(f(X)) = int(x*f(x)) w.r.t. x over the range [-infinity,infinity]
s_dist1:mean.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a unary function denoting the mean of a 
distribution. The argument is a univariate function to describe the 
distribution. That is, if f is the function describing the 
distribution. The mean is the expression integrate(x*f(x)) w.r.t. x over the
range (-infinity,infinity).

s_dist1:sdev.name: sdev
s_dist1:sdev.description:
This symbol represents a unary function denoting the standard
deviation of a distribution. The argument is a univariate function
to describe the distribution. The standard deviation of a distribution
is the arithmetical mean of the squares of the deviation of the
distribution from the mean.
cmp_properties: The standard deviation of a distribution is the arithmetical mean of the squares of the deviation of the distribution from the mean.
s_dist1:sdev.sympy_function: lambda *args: sympy.sqrt(sum((x - sum(args)/len(args))**2 for x in args) / len(args))
s_dist1:sdev.sympy_signature: lambda *args: sympy.sqrt(sum((x - sum(args)/len(args))**2 for x in args) / len(args))
s_dist1:sdev.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a unary function denoting the standard
deviation of a distribution. The argument is a univariate function
to describe the distribution. The standard deviation of a distribution
is the arithmetical mean of the squares of the deviation of the
distribution from the mean.

s_dist1:variance.name: variance
s_dist1:variance.description:
This symbol represents a unary function denoting the variance of a
distribution. The argument is a function to describe the distribution.
That is if f is the function which describes the distribution.
The variance of a distribution is the square of the standard deviation
of the distribution.
cmp_properties: The variance of a distribution is the square of the standard deviation of the distribution.
s_dist1:variance.sympy_function: lambda *args: sum((x - sum(args)/len(args))**2 for x in args) / len(args)
s_dist1:variance.sympy_signature: lambda *args: sum((x - sum(args)/len(args))**2 for x in args) / len(args)
s_dist1:variance.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a unary function denoting the variance of a
distribution. The argument is a function to describe the distribution.
That is if f is the function which describes the distribution.
The variance of a distribution is the square of the standard deviation
of the distribution.

s_dist1:moment.name: moment
s_dist1:moment.description:
This symbol represents a ternary function to denote the i'th moment of a
distribution. The first argument should be the degree of the moment
(that is, for the i'th moment the first argument should be i), the
second argument is the value about which the moment is to be taken and
the third argument is a univariate function to describe the distribution. That
is, if f is the function which describe the distribution. The i'th
moment of f about a is the integral of (x-a)^i*f(x) with respect to x,
over the interval (-infinity,infinity).
cmp_properties: the i'th moment of f(X) about c = integral of (x-c)^i*f(x) with respect to x, over the interval (-infinity,infinity)
s_dist1:moment.sympy_function: lambda data, n: sum(x**n for x in data) / len(data)
s_dist1:moment.sympy_signature: lambda data, n: sum(x**n for x in data) / len(data)
s_dist1:moment.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a ternary function to denote the i'th moment of a
distribution. The first argument should be the degree of the moment
(that is, for the i'th moment the first argument should be i), the
second argument is the value about which the moment is to be taken and
the third argument is a univariate function to describe the distribution. That
is, if f is the function which describe the distribution. The i'th
moment of f about a is the integral of (x-a)^i*f(x) with respect to x,
over the interval (-infinity,infinity).
cmp_properties_normalized: $\mathbb{E}[(X - c)^k] = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} (x - c)^k f(x) \, dx$ (the $k$-th moment of $f(X)$ about $c$)

relation1:eq.name: eq
relation1:eq.description: This symbol represents the binary equality function.
cmp_properties: a=b and b=c implies a=c
examples: An example which represents the statement 1 + 2 = 3. 1 2 3
relation1:eq.description_normalized: This symbol represents the binary equality function.

relation1:lt.name: lt
relation1:lt.description:
This symbol represents the binary less than function which returns
true if the first argument is less than the second, it returns false
otherwise.
cmp_properties: a<b and b<c implies a<c
examples: An example which represents the statement 1 + 2 < 4 1 2 4
relation1:lt.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the binary less than function which returns
true if the first argument is less than the second, it returns false
otherwise.
examples_normalized: An example which represents the statement \(1 + 2 < 4\): \(1 + 2 = 3\) and \(3 < 4\).

relation1:gt.name: gt
relation1:gt.description:
This symbol represents the binary greater than function which returns
true if the first argument is greater than the second, it returns false
otherwise.
cmp_properties: a>b and b>c implies a>c
examples: An example which represents the statement 1 + 2 > 2 1 2 2
relation1:gt.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the binary greater than function which returns
true if the first argument is greater than the second, it returns false
otherwise.
examples_normalized: An example which represents the statement \(1 + 2 > 2 \cdot 2\)

relation1:neq.name: neq
relation1:neq.description: This symbol represents the binary inequality function.
cmp_properties: it is not true that a=/b and b=/c implies a=/c
examples: An example which represents the statement 1 + 2 not = 2 1 2 2
relation1:neq.description_normalized: This symbol represents the binary inequality function.
examples_normalized: An example which represents the statement \(1 + 2 \neq 2122\).

relation1:leq.name: leq
relation1:leq.description:
This symbol represents the binary less than or equal to function which returns
true if the first argument is less than or equal to the second, it
returns false otherwise.
cmp_properties: a<=b and b<=c implies a<=c
examples: An example which represents the statement 1 + 2 <= 4 1 2 4
relation1:leq.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the binary less than or equal to function which returns
true if the first argument is less than or equal to the second, it
returns false otherwise.
examples_normalized: $An example which represents the statement 1 + 2 < = 4 1 2 4$

relation1:geq.name: geq
relation1:geq.description:
This symbol represents the binary greater than or equal to function
which returns true if the first argument is greater than or equal to
the second, it returns false otherwise.
cmp_properties: a>=b and b>=c implies a>=c
examples: An example which represents the statement 1 + 2 >= 3 1 2 3
relation1:geq.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the binary greater than or equal to function
which returns true if the first argument is greater than or equal to
the second, it returns false otherwise.
examples_normalized: $An example which represents the statement 1 + 2 > = 3 1 2 3$

relation1:approx.name: approx
relation1:approx.description: This symbol is used to denote the approximate equality of its two arguments.
examples: \pi is approximately 355/113 355 113
relation1:approx.sympy_function: lambda a, b, tol=1e-9: abs(a - b) < tol
relation1:approx.sympy_signature: lambda a, b, tol=1e-9: abs(a - b) < tol
relation1:approx.description_normalized: This symbol is used to denote the approximate equality of its two arguments.
examples_normalized: $\pi \approx \frac{355}{113}$

scscp1:procedure_call.name: procedure_call
scscp1:procedure_call.description:
The actual procedure call. Its only argument is an OpenMath Application,
      whose head symbol describes the procedure to be called,
      and whose arguments are the arguments to the procedure.
scscp1:procedure_call.description_normalized:
The actual procedure call. Its only argument is an OpenMath Application,
      whose head symbol describes the procedure to be called,
      and whose arguments are the arguments to the procedure.

scscp1:procedure_completed.name: procedure_completed
scscp1:procedure_completed.description:
The result of a successful computation. Should come along 
      with a call_id and, possibly, some extra information.
scscp1:procedure_completed.description_normalized:
The result of a successful computation. Should come along 
      with a call_id and, possibly, some extra information.

scscp1:procedure_terminated.name: procedure_terminated
scscp1:procedure_terminated.description:
The result of a failed computation. Should come along with a call_id, an error
      description, and possibly some extra information.
examples: a24904e5d3ed28eae9225fd787f64a71 21897 Segmentation fault
scscp1:procedure_terminated.description_normalized:
The result of a failed computation. Should come along with a call_id, an error
      description, and possibly some extra information.
examples_normalized: Session terminated with cookie reference

scscp1:call_id.name: call_id
scscp1:call_id.description:
Uniquely identifies a procedure call. Used in subsequent communication, so the
      parties know which call they are talking about.
examples: a1d0c6e83f027327d8461063f4ac58a6 The OMA goes here
scscp1:call_id.description_normalized:
Uniquely identifies a procedure call. Used in subsequent communication, so the

scscp1:option_max_memory.name: option_max_memory
scscp1:option_max_memory.description:
An option, to be given along with a procedure call, describing the maximum amount of
      memory (in bytes) the system should spend on this call.
examples: localhost:26137:18668:s2sYf1pg 20971520 The OMA goes here

scscp1:option_min_memory.name: option_min_memory
scscp1:option_min_memory.description:
An option, to be given along with a procedure call, describing the minimum amount of
      memory (in bytes) the system should be able to spend on this call.  The idea is that
      in certain cases we know in advance that we will need a large amount of memory. If
      the system will never be able to provide that, it would be a waste of time and
      resources to even start the computation.
examples: localhost:26137:18668:s2sYf1pg 250971520 The OMA goes here

scscp1:error_memory.name: error_memory
scscp1:error_memory.description:
A description of the error that caused a procedure call to be terminated. This
      symbol is used with a procedure_terminated, when the system exceeded the amount of
      memory specified in the option_max_memory option given in the corresponding
      procedure call.

      It carries one argument: An OMSTR, which may be empty.
scscp1:error_memory.description_normalized:
A description of the error that caused a procedure call to be terminated. This
      symbol is used with a procedure_terminated, when the system exceeded the amount of
      memory specified in the option_max_memory option given in the corresponding
      procedure call.

      It carries one argument: An OMSTR, which may be empty.

scscp1:error_runtime.name: error_runtime
scscp1:error_runtime.description:
A description of the error that caused a procedure call to be terminated. This
      symbol is used with a procedure_terminated, when the system exceeded the runtime
      specified in the option_runtime option given in the corresponding procedure call.

      It carries one argument: An OMSTR, which may be empty.

      Note that this symbol is not intended to be used when a different runtime error
      occurred.  In those cases, one should use error_system_specific.
scscp1:error_runtime.description_normalized:
A description of the error that caused a procedure call to be terminated. This

scscp1:error_system_specific.name: error_system_specific
scscp1:error_system_specific.description:
A description of the error that caused a procedure call to be terminated. This
      symbol is used with a procedure_terminated, when the error is specific to the system
      that carried out the calculation.  This error must carry exactly one argument, and
      it must be an OMSTR describing the error that occurred.
scscp1:error_system_specific.description_normalized:

      it must be an OMSTR describing the error that occurred.

error:unhandled_symbol.name: unhandled_symbol
error:unhandled_symbol.description:
This symbol represents the error which is raised when an application
reads a symbol which is present in the mentioned content
dictionary, but which it has not implemented.

When receiving such a symbol, the application should act as if it had
received the OpenMath error object constructed from unhandled_symbol
and the unhandled symbol as in the example below.
examples: The application does not implement the Complex numbers:

quant1:forall.name: forall
quant1:forall.description:
This symbol represents the universal ("for all") quantifier which takes two
arguments. It must be placed within an OMBIND element. The first argument is the
bound variables (placed within an OMBVAR element), and the second is an expression.
examples: An example to represent the statement for all real x, |sin(x)| <= 1
quant1:forall.sympy_function: lambda var, pred: sympy.ForAll(var, pred) if hasattr(sympy, 'ForAll') else ('forall', var, pred)
quant1:forall.sympy_signature: lambda var, pred: sympy.ForAll(var, pred) if hasattr(sympy, 'ForAll') else ('forall', var, pred)
quant1:forall.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the universal ("for all") quantifier which takes two
arguments. It must be placed within an OMBIND element. The first argument is the
bound variables (placed within an OMBVAR element), and the second is an expression.
examples_normalized: $\forall x \in \mathbb{R}: |\sin(x)| \leq 1$

quant1:exists.name: exists
quant1:exists.description:
This symbol represents the existential ("there exists") quantifier
which takes two arguments. It must be placed within an OMBIND element. The first
argument is the bound variables (placed within an OMBVAR element), and the second
is an expression.
examples: An example which represents the statement that there is no solution to x^n+y^n=z^n for n>2, that is: it is not true that there exists x,y,z,n | n>2 and x^n+y^n=z^n 2
quant1:exists.sympy_function: lambda var, pred: sympy.Exists(var, pred) if hasattr(sympy, 'Exists') else ('exists', var, pred)
quant1:exists.sympy_signature: lambda var, pred: sympy.Exists(var, pred) if hasattr(sympy, 'Exists') else ('exists', var, pred)
quant1:exists.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the existential ("there exists") quantifier
which takes two arguments. It must be placed within an OMBIND element. The first
argument is the bound variables (placed within an OMBVAR element), and the second
is an expression.
examples_normalized: $\neg \exists x, y, z, n \mid n > 2 \text{ and } x^n + y^n = z^n$

setname1:P.name: P
setname1:P.description: This symbol represents the set of positive prime numbers.
cmp_properties: for all n | n is a positive prime number is equivalent to: n is a natural number and n > 1 and ((n=a*b and a and b are natural numbers) implies ((a=1 and b=n) or (b=1 and a=n)))
setname1:P.description_normalized: This symbol represents the set of positive prime numbers.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\forall n \mid n is a positive \mathbb{p} is \triangleq: n is a natural number \wedge n > 1 \wedge ((n=a \cdot b \wedge a \wedge b are \mathbb{N}) \Rightarrow ((a=1 \wedge b=n) \vee (b=1 \wedge a=n)))$

setname1:N.name: N
setname1:N.description: This symbol represents the set of natural numbers (including zero).
cmp_properties: for all n | n in the natural numbers is equivalent to saying n=0 or n-1 is a natural number
setname1:N.description_normalized: This symbol represents the set of natural numbers (including zero).
cmp_properties_normalized: $\forall n \mid n in the \mathbb{N} is \triangleq saying n=0 \vee n-1 is a natural number$

setname1:Z.name: Z
setname1:Z.description: This symbol represents the set of integers, positive, negative and zero.
cmp_properties: for all z | the statements z is an integer and z is a natural number or -z is a natural number are equivalent
setname1:Z.description_normalized: This symbol represents the set of integers, positive, negative and zero.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\forall z \mid the statements z is an integer \wedge z is a natural number \vee -z is a natural number are equivalent$

setname1:Q.name: Q
setname1:Q.description: This  symbol represents the set of rational numbers.
cmp_properties: for all z where z is a rational, there exists integers p and q with q > 1 and p/q = z
for all a,b | a,b rational with a<b implies there exists rational a,c s.t. a<c and c<b
setname1:Q.description_normalized: This  symbol represents the set of rational numbers.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\forall z where z is a rational, \exists \mathbb{Z} p \wedge q with q > 1 \wedge p/q = z$
$\forall a,b \mid a,b rational with a<b \Rightarrow \exists rational a,c s.t. a<c \wedge c<b$

setname1:R.name: R
setname1:R.description: This symbol represents the set of real numbers.
cmp_properties: S \subset R and exists y in R : forall x in S x <= y) implies exists z in R such that (( forall x in S x <= z) and ((forall x in S x <= w) implies z <= w)
setname1:R.description_normalized: This symbol represents the set of real numbers.
cmp_properties_normalized: $S \subseteq R$ and $\exists y \in R : \forall x \in S, x \leq y)$ implies $\exists z \in R$ such that $(\forall x \in S, x \leq z)$ and $(\forall x \in S, x \leq w) \implies z \leq w)$

setname1:C.name: C
setname1:C.description: This  symbol represents the set of complex numbers.
cmp_properties: for all z | if z is complex then there exist reals x,y s.t. z = x + i * y
setname1:C.description_normalized: This  symbol represents the set of complex numbers.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\forall z \mid if z is complex then \exists reals x,y s.t. z = x + i \cdot y$

piece1:piecewise.name: piecewise
piece1:piecewise.description:
This operator heads an expression that is being defined piecewise. Its 
arguments are n objects built with the piece constructor, optionally
followed by one built with otherwise constructor.
piece1:piecewise.description_normalized:
This operator heads an expression that is being defined piecewise. Its 
arguments are n objects built with the piece constructor, optionally
followed by one built with otherwise constructor.
examples_normalized: $0 \cdot 0 \cdot 0$

piece1:piece.name: piece
piece1:piece.description:
This introduces an individual component of a piecewise definition. It has
precisely two arguments: the first is the value, and the second is a Boolean
(meant to be a predicate) which is true if and only if this piece is to
provide the value of the piecewise construct.
piece1:piece.description_normalized:
This introduces an individual component of a piecewise definition. It has
precisely two arguments: the first is the value, and the second is a Boolean
(meant to be a predicate) which is true if and only if this piece is to
provide the value of the piecewise construct.
examples_normalized: $0 \cdot 0 \cdot 0$

piece1:otherwise.name: otherwise
piece1:otherwise.description:
This symbol introduces the 'default' value of a piecewise construct.
If none of the previous piece constructs can provide the value, this will.
It has a single child, the value.
piece1:otherwise.description_normalized:
This symbol introduces the 'default' value of a piecewise construct.
If none of the previous piece constructs can provide the value, this will.
It has a single child, the value.
examples_normalized: $0 \cdot 0 \cdot 0$

set1:cartesian_product.name: cartesian_product
set1:cartesian_product.description:
This symbol represents an n-ary construction function for constructing
the Cartesian product of sets. It takes n set arguments in order to
construct their Cartesian product.
examples: An example to show the representation of the Cartesian product of sets: AxBxC.
set1:cartesian_product.description_normalized:
This symbol represents an n-ary construction function for constructing
the Cartesian product of sets. It takes n set arguments in order to
construct their Cartesian product.
examples_normalized: An example to show the representation of the Cartesian product of sets: AxBxC.
cmp_properties_normalized: $A \times B = \{(a, b) \mid a \in A \wedge b \in B\}$

set1:emptyset.name: emptyset
set1:emptyset.description:
This symbol is used to represent the empty set, that is the set which
contains no members. It takes no parameters.
cmp_properties: The intersection of A with the emptyset is the emptyset
The union of A with the emptyset is A
the size of the empty set is zero
set1:emptyset.description_normalized:
This symbol is used to represent the empty set, that is the set which
contains no members. It takes no parameters.
cmp_properties_normalized: The intersection of A with the emptyset is the emptyset
The union of A with the emptyset is A
the size of the empty set is zero

set1:map.name: map
set1:map.description:
This symbol represents a mapping function which may be used to
construct sets, it takes as arguments a function from X to Y and a
set over X in that order. The value that is returned is a set of
values in Y. The argument list may be a set or an integer_interval.
examples: The set of even values between 0 and 20, that is the values 2x, where x ranges over the integral interval [0,10]. 2 0 10
set1:map.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a mapping function which may be used to
construct sets, it takes as arguments a function from X to Y and a
set over X in that order. The value that is returned is a set of
values in Y. The argument list may be a set or an integer_interval.
examples_normalized: The set of even values between 0 and 20, that is the values 2x, where x ranges over the integral interval [0,10]. $2 \cdot 0, 2 \cdot 1, 2 \cdot 2, \ldots, 2 \cdot 10$

set1:size.name: size
set1:size.description:
This symbol is used to denote the number of elements in a set. It is
either a non-negative integer, or an infinite cardinal number. The
symbol infinity may be used for an unspecified infinite cardinal.
examples: The size of the set{3,6,9} = 3 3 6 9 3
The size of the set of integers is infinite
set1:size.sympy_function: lambda S: S.measure if hasattr(S, 'measure') else len(S)
set1:size.sympy_signature: lambda S: S.measure if hasattr(S, 'measure') else len(S)
set1:size.description_normalized:
This symbol is used to denote the number of elements in a set. It is
either a non-negative integer, or an infinite cardinal number. The
symbol infinity may be used for an unspecified infinite cardinal.
examples_normalized: The size of the set of integers is infinite

set1:suchthat.name: suchthat
set1:suchthat.description:
This symbol represents the suchthat function which may be used to
construct sets, it takes two arguments. The first argument should be the
set which contains the elements of the set we wish to represent, the
second argument should be a predicate, that is a function from the set
to the booleans which describes if an element is to be in the set returned.
examples: This example shows how to construct the set of even integers, using the suchthat constructor. 2
set1:suchthat.sympy_function: lambda S, pred: S & sympy.ConditionSet(sympy.Symbol('x'), pred, S)
set1:suchthat.sympy_signature: lambda S, pred: S & sympy.ConditionSet(sympy.Symbol('x'), pred, S)
set1:suchthat.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the suchthat function which may be used to
construct sets, it takes two arguments. The first argument should be the
set which contains the elements of the set we wish to represent, the
second argument should be a predicate, that is a function from the set
to the booleans which describes if an element is to be in the set returned.
examples_normalized: This example shows how to construct the set of even integers, using the suchthat constructor. 2

set1:set.name: set
set1:set.description:
This symbol represents the set construct. It is an n-ary function. The
set entries are given explicitly. There is no implied ordering to the
elements of a set.
set1:set.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the set construct. It is an n-ary function. The
set entries are given explicitly. There is no implied ordering to the
elements of a set.

set1:intersect.name: intersect
set1:intersect.description:
This symbol is used to denote the n-ary intersection of sets. It takes
sets as arguments, and denotes the set that contains all the
elements that occur in all of them.
cmp_properties: (A intersect B) is a subset of A and (A intersect B) is a subset of B
set1:intersect.description_normalized:
This symbol is used to denote the n-ary intersection of sets. It takes
sets as arguments, and denotes the set that contains all the
elements that occur in all of them.

set1:union.name: union
set1:union.description:
This symbol is used to denote the n-ary union of sets. It takes
sets as arguments, and denotes the set that contains all the
elements that occur in any of them.
cmp_properties: A is a subset of (A union B) and B is a subset of (A union B)
for all sets A,B and C union(A,intersect(B,C)) = intersect(union(A,B),union(A,C))
set1:union.description_normalized:
This symbol is used to denote the n-ary union of sets. It takes
sets as arguments, and denotes the set that contains all the
elements that occur in any of them.

set1:setdiff.name: setdiff
set1:setdiff.description:
This symbol is used to denote the set difference of two sets. It takes
two sets as arguments, and denotes the set that contains all the
elements that occur in the first set, but not in the second.
cmp_properties: the difference of A and B is a subset of A
set1:setdiff.description_normalized:
This symbol is used to denote the set difference of two sets. It takes
two sets as arguments, and denotes the set that contains all the
elements that occur in the first set, but not in the second.

set1:subset.name: subset
set1:subset.description:
This symbol has two (set) arguments. It is used to denote that the
first set is a subset of the second.
cmp_properties: if B is a subset of A and C is a subset of B then C is a subset of A
set1:subset.description_normalized:
This symbol has two (set) arguments. It is used to denote that the
first set is a subset of the second.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\forall A, B, C \mid B \subseteq A \land C \subseteq B \implies C \subseteq A$

set1:in.name: in
set1:in.description:
This symbol has two arguments, an element and a set. It is used to
denote that the element is in the given set.
cmp_properties: if a is in A and a is in B then a is in A intersect B
set1:in.sympy_function: lambda x, S: x in S
set1:in.sympy_signature: lambda x, S: x in S
set1:in.description_normalized:
This symbol has two arguments, an element and a set. It is used to
denote that the element is in the given set.
cmp_properties_normalized: if a is in A and a is in B then a is in A intersect B

set1:notin.name: notin
set1:notin.description:
This symbol has two arguments, an element and a set. It is used to
denote that the element is not in the given set.
cmp_properties: if a is a member of a then it is not true that a is not a member of A
set1:notin.sympy_function: lambda x, S: x not in S
set1:notin.sympy_signature: lambda x, S: x not in S
set1:notin.description_normalized:
This symbol has two arguments, an element and a set. It is used to
denote that the element is not in the given set.
cmp_properties_normalized: if a is a member of a then it is not true that a is not a member of A

set1:prsubset.name: prsubset
set1:prsubset.description:
This symbol has two (set) arguments. It is used to denote that the
first set is a proper subset of the second, that is a subset of the
second set but not actually equal to it.
cmp_properties: A is a proper subset of B implies that A is a subset of B and A not= B
examples: {2,3} is a proper subset of {1,2,3} 2 3 1 2 3
set1:prsubset.description_normalized:
This symbol has two (set) arguments. It is used to denote that the
first set is a proper subset of the second, that is a subset of the
second set but not actually equal to it.
cmp_properties_normalized: $A is a proper subset of B implies that A is a subset of B and A not = B$

set1:notsubset.name: notsubset
set1:notsubset.description:
This symbol has two (set) arguments. It is used to denote that the
first set is not a subset of the second.
cmp_properties: if A is not a subset of B then there exists an x in B s.t. x is not a member of B
examples: {2,3,4} is not a subset of {1,2,3} 2 3 4 1 2 3
set1:notsubset.description_normalized:
This symbol has two (set) arguments. It is used to denote that the
first set is not a subset of the second.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\neg (A \subseteq B) \implies \exists x \in B \text{ such that } x \notin A$

set1:notprsubset.name: notprsubset
set1:notprsubset.description:
This symbol has two (set) arguments. It is used to denote that the
first set is not a proper subset of the second. A proper subset of a
set is a subset of the set but not actually equal to it.
cmp_properties: A is not a proper subset of B implies that it is not true that A is a proper subset of B
examples: {1,2,3} is not a proper subset of {1,2,3} 1 2 3 1 2 3
set1:notprsubset.description_normalized:
This symbol has two (set) arguments. It is used to denote that the
first set is not a proper subset of the second. A proper subset of a
set is a subset of the set but not actually equal to it.

bigfloat1:bigfloat.name: bigfloat
bigfloat1:bigfloat.description:
The bigfloat constructor takes three arguments, a mantissa, a base and the
exponent.
cmp_properties: bigfloat(m,r,e)=m*r^e
bigfloat1:bigfloat.description_normalized:
The bigfloat constructor takes three arguments, a mantissa, a base and the
exponent.

bigfloat1:bigfloatprec.name: bigfloatprec
bigfloat1:bigfloatprec.description:
The bigfloat "with precision specified in (another) radix" constructor. Takes 
3 arguments, the first argument is a floating point number constructed with the
bigfloat constructor, the second is the new radix, whilst the third specifies 
how many digits are significant.
cmp_properties: bigfloatprec(f,r,p)=f However, if converted to radix r, only p digits in that radix are significant. This usually means that it originated in radix r, and has since (e.g. for display purposes) been converted into its current radix. For exposition, f = m*r^e.
bigfloat1:bigfloatprec.description_normalized:
The bigfloat "with precision specified in (another) radix" constructor. Takes 
3 arguments, the first argument is a floating point number constructed with the
bigfloat constructor, the second is the new radix, whilst the third specifies 
how many digits are significant.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\operatorname{bigfloatprec}(f,r,p) = f$ However, if converted to radix r, only p digits in that radix are significant. This usually means that it originated in radix r, and has since (e.g. for display purposes) been converted into its current radix. For exposition, f = m*r^e.

alg1:zero.name: zero
alg1:zero.description: This symbol represents the additive identity element.
cmp_properties: for all a | a + 0 = a
for all a | 0 * a = 0
The zero of the integers is 0
alg1:zero.description_normalized: This symbol represents the additive identity element.
cmp_properties_normalized: The zero of the integers is 0

alg1:one.name: one
alg1:one.description: This symbol represents the multiplicative identity element.
cmp_properties: for all a | 1 * a = a
for all a | a * 1 = a
The one of the integers is 1
alg1:one.description_normalized: This symbol represents the multiplicative identity element.
cmp_properties_normalized: The one of the integers is 1

veccalc1:divergence.name: divergence
veccalc1:divergence.description:
This symbol is used to represent the divergence function. It takes one
argument which should be a vector of scalar valued functions,
intended to represent a vector valued function and returns a
scalar value. It should satisfy the defining relation:
 divergence(F) = \partial(F_(x_1))/\partial(x_1) + ...
 + \partial(F_(x_n))/\partial(x_n)
cmp_properties: divergence(F) = \partial(F_(x_1))/\partial(x_1) + ... + \partial(F_(x_n))/\partial(x_n)
veccalc1:divergence.sympy_function: lambda F, vars: sum(sympy.diff(F[i], vars[i]) for i in range(len(vars)))
veccalc1:divergence.sympy_signature: lambda F, vars: sum(sympy.diff(F[i], vars[i]) for i in range(len(vars)))
veccalc1:divergence.description_normalized:
This symbol is used to represent the divergence function. It takes one
argument which should be a vector of scalar valued functions,
intended to represent a vector valued function and returns a
scalar value. It should satisfy the defining relation:
 divergence(F) = \partial(F_(x_1))/\partial(x_1) + ...
 + \partial(F_(x_n))/\partial(x_n)

veccalc1:grad.name: grad
veccalc1:grad.description:
This symbol is used to represent the grad function. It takes one
argument which should be a scalar valued function and returns a
vector of functions. It should satisfy the defining relation:
grad(F) = (\partial(F)/\partial(x_1), ... ,\partial(F)/partial(x_n))
cmp_properties: grad(F) = (\partial(F)/\partial(x_1), ... ,\partial(F)/partial(x_n))
veccalc1:grad.sympy_function: lambda f, vars: sympy.Matrix([sympy.diff(f, v) for v in vars])
veccalc1:grad.sympy_signature: lambda f, vars: sympy.Matrix([sympy.diff(f, v) for v in vars])
veccalc1:grad.description_normalized:
This symbol is used to represent the grad function. It takes one
argument which should be a scalar valued function and returns a
vector of functions. It should satisfy the defining relation:
grad(F) = (\partial(F)/\partial(x_1), ... ,\partial(F)/partial(x_n))

veccalc1:curl.name: curl
veccalc1:curl.description:
This symbol is used to represent the curl function. It takes one
argument which should be a vector of scalar valued functions, intended
to represent a vector valued function and returns a vector of
functions. It should satisfy the defining relation:
curl(F) = i X \partial(F)/\partial(x) + j X \partial(F)/\partial(y) +
j X \partial(F)/\partial(Z) where i,j,k are the unit vectors
corresponding to the x,y,z axes respectively and the multiplication X
is cross multiplication.
cmp_properties: curl(F) = i X \partial(F)/\partial(x) + j X \partial(F)/\partial(y) + j X \partial(F)/\partial(Z)
veccalc1:curl.sympy_function: lambda F, vars: sympy.Matrix([sympy.diff(F[2], vars[1]) - sympy.diff(F[1], vars[2]), sympy.diff(F[0], vars[2]) - sympy.diff(F[2], vars[0]), sympy.diff(F[1], vars[0]) - sympy.diff(F[0], vars[1])])
veccalc1:curl.sympy_signature: lambda F, vars: sympy.Matrix([sympy.diff(F[2], vars[1]) - sympy.diff(F[1], vars[2]), sympy.diff(F[0], vars[2]) - sympy.diff(F[2], vars[0]), sympy.diff(F[1], vars[0]) - sympy.diff(F[0], vars[1])])
veccalc1:curl.description_normalized:
This symbol is used to represent the curl function. It takes one
argument which should be a vector of scalar valued functions, intended
to represent a vector valued function and returns a vector of
functions. It should satisfy the defining relation:
curl(F) = i X \partial(F)/\partial(x) + j X \partial(F)/\partial(y) +
j X \partial(F)/\partial(Z) where i,j,k are the unit vectors
corresponding to the x,y,z axes respectively and the multiplication X
is cross multiplication.

veccalc1:Laplacian.name: Laplacian
veccalc1:Laplacian.description:
This symbol is used to represent the laplacian function. It takes one
argument which should be a vector of scalar valued functions, intended
to represent a vector valued function and returns a vector of
functions. It should satisfy the defining relation:
laplacian(F) = \partial^2(F)/\partial(x_1)^2 + ... +
\partial^2(F)/\partial(x_n)^2
cmp_properties: laplacian(F) = \partial^2(F)/\partial(x_1)^2 + ... + \partial^2(F)/\partial(x_n)^2
veccalc1:Laplacian.sympy_function: lambda f, vars: sum(sympy.diff(f, v, 2) for v in vars)
veccalc1:Laplacian.sympy_signature: lambda f, vars: sum(sympy.diff(f, v, 2) for v in vars)
veccalc1:Laplacian.description_normalized:
This symbol is used to represent the laplacian function. It takes one
argument which should be a vector of scalar valued functions, intended
to represent a vector valued function and returns a vector of
functions. It should satisfy the defining relation:
laplacian(F) = \partial^2(F)/\partial(x_1)^2 + ... +
\partial^2(F)/\partial(x_n)^2

mathmltypes:type.name: type
mathmltypes:type.description:
A symbol to be used within an OpenMath attribute to specify the type of
the object.
examples: The variable z is attributed with a type for complex numbers, to be represented in polar notation.
mathmltypes:type.description_normalized:
A symbol to be used within an OpenMath attribute to specify the type of
the object.
examples_normalized: The variable z is attributed with a type for complex numbers, to be represented in polar notation.

mathmltypes:integer_type.name: integer_type
mathmltypes:integer_type.description:

type of an integer.
examples: The variable z is attributed with a type for integers.
mathmltypes:integer_type.description_normalized:
A symbol to be used as the argument of the type symbol to convey the

mathmltypes:complex_cartesian_type.description:

mathmltypes:constant_type.name: constant_type
mathmltypes:constant_type.description:
A symbol to be used as the argument of the type symbol to convey a
type for the common constants, pi ~= 3.1415, e ~= 2.718, i = square
root of -1, gamma ~= .5772, NaN, infinity (all in the nums cd), true
and false (in the logic cd). Also for MathML variables declared to
have type constant, as in <ci type="constant">x</ci>.
examples: The variable z is attributed with a type for constants.

mathmltypes:fn_type.description_normalized:
A symbol to be used as the argument of the type symbol to convey the

logic1:equivalent.name: equivalent
logic1:equivalent.description:
This symbol is used to show that two boolean expressions are logically 
equivalent, that is have the same boolean value for any inputs.
cmp_properties: The condition (A is equivalent to B) is equivalent to the condition that (A implies B and B implies A)
logic1:equivalent.description_normalized:
This symbol is used to show that two boolean expressions are logically 
equivalent, that is have the same boolean value for any inputs.

logic1:not.name: not
logic1:not.description:
This symbol represents the logical not function which takes one boolean
argument, and returns the opposite boolean value.
cmp_properties: for all x | not(not(x))=x
logic1:not.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the logical not function which takes one boolean
argument, and returns the opposite boolean value.

logic1:and.name: and
logic1:and.description:
This symbol represents the logical and function which is an n-ary
function taking boolean arguments and returning a boolean value. It
is true if all arguments are true or false otherwise.
cmp_properties: for all x | x and not(x) = false
logic1:and.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the logical and function which is an n-ary
function taking boolean arguments and returning a boolean value. It
is true if all arguments are true or false otherwise.

logic1:nand.name: nand
logic1:nand.description:
This symbol represents the logical nand function which is an n-ary
function taking boolean arguments and returning a boolean value. It
is false if all arguments are true or true otherwise.
cmp_properties: for all x | x nand not(x) = true
logic1:nand.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the logical nand function which is an n-ary
function taking boolean arguments and returning a boolean value. It
is false if all arguments are true or true otherwise.

logic1:xor.name: xor
logic1:xor.description:
This symbol represents the logical xor function which is an n-ary
function taking boolean arguments and returning a boolean
value. It is true if there are an odd number of true arguments or
false otherwise.
cmp_properties: for all x | x xor x = false
for all x | x xor not(x) = true
logic1:xor.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the logical xor function which is an n-ary
function taking boolean arguments and returning a boolean
value. It is true if there are an odd number of true arguments or
false otherwise.

logic1:xnor.name: xnor
logic1:xnor.description:
This symbol represents the logical xnor function which is an n-ary
function taking boolean arguments and returning a boolean
value. It is false if there are an odd number of true arguments or
true otherwise.
cmp_properties: for all x | x xnor x = true
for all x | x xnor not(x) = false
logic1:xnor.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the logical xnor function which is an n-ary
function taking boolean arguments and returning a boolean
value. It is false if there are an odd number of true arguments or
true otherwise.

logic1:or.name: or
logic1:or.description:
This symbol represents the logical or function which is an n-ary
function taking boolean arguments and returning a boolean value. It
is true if any of the arguments are true or false otherwise.
cmp_properties: for all x | x or not(x) = true
for all a,b | not(a and b)= (not(a) or not(b))
logic1:or.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the logical or function which is an n-ary
function taking boolean arguments and returning a boolean value. It
is true if any of the arguments are true or false otherwise.

logic1:nor.name: nor
logic1:nor.description:
This symbol represents the logical nor function which is an n-ary
function taking boolean arguments and returning a boolean value. It
is false if any of the arguments are true or true otherwise.
cmp_properties: for all x | x nor not(x) = false
for all a,b | a and b = (not(a) nor not(b))
logic1:nor.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the logical nor function which is an n-ary
function taking boolean arguments and returning a boolean value. It
is false if any of the arguments are true or true otherwise.

logic1:implies.name: implies
logic1:implies.description:
This symbol represents the logical implies function which takes two
boolean expressions as arguments. It evaluates to false if the first
argument is true and the second argument is false, otherwise it
evaluates to true.
cmp_properties: for all x | false implies x
logic1:implies.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the logical implies function which takes two
boolean expressions as arguments. It evaluates to false if the first
argument is true and the second argument is false, otherwise it
evaluates to true.

logic1:true.name: true
logic1:true.description: This symbol represents the boolean value true.
cmp_properties: not true = false
logic1:true.description_normalized: This symbol represents the boolean value true.

logic1:false.name: false
logic1:false.description: This symbol represents the boolean value false.
cmp_properties: not false = true
logic1:false.description_normalized: This symbol represents the boolean value false.

linalg2:vector.name: vector
linalg2:vector.description:
This symbol represents an n-ary function used to construct (or describe)
vectors.  Vectors in this CD are considered to be row vectors and must 
therefore be transposed to be considered as column vectors.
examples: An example of vector using n arguments. The specific vector constructed in this example is [3,6,9]. 3 6 9
linalg2:vector.description_normalized:
This symbol represents an n-ary function used to construct (or describe)
vectors.  Vectors in this CD are considered to be row vectors and must 
therefore be transposed to be considered as column vectors.
examples_normalized: An example of vector using n arguments. The specific vector constructed in this example is [3,6,9]. 3 6 9

linalg2:matrixrow.name: matrixrow
linalg2:matrixrow.description:
This symbol is an n-ary constructor used to represent rows of
matrices. Its arguments should be members of a ring.
examples: Representation of a row of a matrix of length two containing the integers [1,0] 1 0
linalg2:matrixrow.description_normalized:
This symbol is an n-ary constructor used to represent rows of
matrices. Its arguments should be members of a ring.
examples_normalized: Representation of a row of a matrix of length two containing the integers [1,0] 1 0

linalg2:matrix.name: matrix
linalg2:matrix.description:
This symbol is an n-ary matrix constructor which requires matrixrow's
as arguments. It is used to represent matrices.
examples: Representation of a 2x2 identity matrix 1 0 0 1
linalg2:matrix.description_normalized:
This symbol is an n-ary matrix constructor which requires matrixrow's
as arguments. It is used to represent matrices.
examples_normalized: A $2 \times 2$ identity matrix: $\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}$

complex1:complex_cartesian.name: complex_cartesian
complex1:complex_cartesian.description:
This symbol represents a constructor function for complex numbers
specified as the Cartesian coordinates of the relevant point on the
complex plane. It takes two arguments, the first is a number x to
denote the real part and the second a number y to denote the imaginary
part of the complex number x + i y. (Where i is the square root of -1.)
cmp_properties: for all x,y | complex_cartesian(x,y) = x + iy
complex1:complex_cartesian.sympy_function: lambda re, im: re + sympy.I * im
complex1:complex_cartesian.sympy_signature: lambda re, im: re + sympy.I * im
complex1:complex_cartesian.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a constructor function for complex numbers
specified as the Cartesian coordinates of the relevant point on the
complex plane. It takes two arguments, the first is a number x to
denote the real part and the second a number y to denote the imaginary
part of the complex number x + i y. (Where i is the square root of -1.)

complex1:real.name: real
complex1:real.description: This represents the real part of a complex number
cmp_properties: for all x,y | x = real(x+iy)
complex1:real.description_normalized: This represents the real part of a complex number

complex1:imaginary.name: imaginary
complex1:imaginary.description: This represents the imaginary part of a complex number
cmp_properties: for all x,y | y = imaginary(x+iy)
complex1:imaginary.description_normalized: This represents the imaginary part of a complex number

complex1:complex_polar.name: complex_polar
complex1:complex_polar.description:
This symbol represents a constructor function for complex numbers
specified as the polar coordinates of the relevant point on the complex
plane. It takes two arguments, the first is a nonnegative number r to
denote the magnitude and the second a number theta (given in radians)
to denote the argument of the complex number r e^(i theta). (i and
e are defined as in this CD).
cmp_properties: for all r,a | complex_polar(r,a) = r*e^(a*i)
for all x,y,r,a | (r sin a = y and r cos a = x) implies (complex_polar(r,a) = complex_cartesian(x,y)
for all x | if a is a real number and k is an integer then complex_polar(x,a) = complex_polar(x,a+2*pi*k)
examples: i = complex_polar(1,pi/2) 2
complex1:complex_polar.sympy_function: lambda r, theta: r * sympy.exp(sympy.I * theta)
complex1:complex_polar.sympy_signature: lambda r, theta: r * sympy.exp(sympy.I * theta)
complex1:complex_polar.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a constructor function for complex numbers
specified as the polar coordinates of the relevant point on the complex
plane. It takes two arguments, the first is a nonnegative number r to
denote the magnitude and the second a number theta (given in radians)
to denote the argument of the complex number r e^(i theta). (i and
e are defined as in this CD).
cmp_properties_normalized: $\forall x,y,r,a \mid (r sin a = y \wedge r cos a = x) \Rightarrow (complex_polar(r,a) = complex_cartesian(x,y)$
$\forall x \mid if a is a real number \wedge k is an integer then complex_polar(x,a) = complex_polar(x,a+2 \cdot \mathsfbf{\pi} \cdot k)$
examples_normalized: $i = complex_{polar} \left( 1, \  \frac{\pi}{2}\right) 2$

complex1:argument.name: argument
complex1:argument.description:
This symbol represents the unary function which returns the argument
of a complex number, viz. the angle which a straight line drawn from
the number to zero makes with the Real line (measured
anti-clockwise). The argument to the symbol is the complex number whos
argument is being taken.
cmp_properties: for all r,a | argument(complex_polar(r,a)=a)
the argument of x+i*y = arctan(y/x) (if x is positive)
the argument of x+i*y = arctan(y,x) (two-argument arctan from transc2)
complex1:argument.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the unary function which returns the argument
of a complex number, viz. the angle which a straight line drawn from
the number to zero makes with the Real line (measured
anti-clockwise). The argument to the symbol is the complex number whos
argument is being taken.

complex1:conjugate.name: conjugate
complex1:conjugate.description: A unary operator representing the complex conjugate of its argument.
cmp_properties: if a is a complex number then (conjugate(a) + a) is a real number
complex1:conjugate.description_normalized: A unary operator representing the complex conjugate of its argument.

minmax1:min.name: min
minmax1:min.description:
This symbol denotes the unary minimum function which takes a set as
 its argument and returns the minimum element in that set.
examples: Representation of the equation minimum{1,9,5} = 1. 1 9 5 1
minmax1:min.description_normalized:
This symbol denotes the unary minimum function which takes a set as
 its argument and returns the minimum element in that set.

minmax1:max.name: max
minmax1:max.description:
This symbol denotes the unary maximum function which takes a set as
 its argument and returns the maximum element in that set.
examples: Representation of the equation maximum{1,9,5} = 9. 1 9 5 9
minmax1:max.description_normalized:
This symbol denotes the unary maximum function which takes a set as
 its argument and returns the maximum element in that set.

sts:nary.description:

examples: The signature for list, an n-ary function:

sts:nassoc.name: nassoc
sts:nassoc.description:
Constructs a child of mapsto which denotes an arbitrary number of
copies of the argument of nassoc. The operator is associative on these
arguments which means that repeated uses may be flattened/unflattened.
examples: The signature for plus, an associative n-ary function:
sts:nassoc.description_normalized:
Constructs a child of mapsto which denotes an arbitrary number of
copies of the argument of nassoc. The operator is associative on these
arguments which means that repeated uses may be flattened/unflattened.
examples_normalized: The signature for plus, an associative n-ary function: $f(a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_n) = a_1 + a_2 + \cdots + a_n$

sts:error.name: error
sts:error.description:
The error symbol is the 'return type' of error symbols in the error
signature file.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0" cdbase="http://www.openmath.org/cd"> <ns1:OMA> <ns1:OMS cd="sts" name="mapsto" /> <ns1:OMV name="OMSymbol" /> <ns1:OMS name="error" cd="sts" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
sts:error.description_normalized:
The error symbol is the 'return type' of error symbols in the error
signature file.
examples_normalized: This symbol represents the natural logarithm function.

which can only be used as the first child of an OMBIND construct.

sts:attribution.name: attribution
sts:attribution.description:
An `attribution' object consists of pairs of keys and values.  The use
of the symbol `attribution' in a signature indicates that the symbol
is to be used as a key.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0" cdbase="http://www.openmath.org/cd"> <ns1:OMS name="attribution" cd="sts" /> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>

of the symbol `attribution' in a signature indicates that the symbol
is to be used as a key.
