graph1:graph.name: graph
graph1:graph.description:
This symbol represents an undirected graph. It takes two
    arguments: the vertex set of the graph and the edge set. 
   The vertices can be arbitrary OpenMath objects. Each edge should be a set consisting of two vertices.
examples: A path of length 2. 1 2 3 1 2 2 3
graph1:graph.description_normalized:
This symbol represents an undirected graph. It takes two
    arguments: the vertex set of the graph and the edge set. 
   The vertices can be arbitrary OpenMath objects. Each edge should be a set consisting of two vertices.
examples_normalized: A path graph of length 2: vertices $\{1, 2, 3\}$ with edges $\{(1,2), (2,3)\}$

graph1:vertexset.name: vertexset
graph1:vertexset.description: This symbol represents the vertex set of a (directed or undirected) graph. It takes one argument, the graph.
examples: If Gamma is a graph, the following function tests whether its argument v is a vertex of Gamma.
graph1:vertexset.description_normalized: This symbol represents the vertex set of a (directed or undirected) graph. It takes one argument, the graph.
examples_normalized: If Gamma is a graph, the following function tests whether its argument v is a vertex of Gamma.

graph1:edgeset.name: edgeset
graph1:edgeset.description: This symbol represents the set of edges of an undirected graph. It takes one argument, the undirected graph.
cmp_properties: Every edge in an undirected graph Gamma is a subset of the vertex set of size two.
examples: Given a graph Gamma and two of its vertices v and w, this predicate asserts that they are adjacent.
graph1:edgeset.description_normalized: This symbol represents the set of edges of an undirected graph. It takes one argument, the undirected graph.
cmp_properties_normalized: Every edge in an undirected graph $\Gamma$ is a subset of the vertex set of size two.
examples_normalized: Given a graph Gamma and two of its vertices v and w, this predicate asserts that they are adjacent.

graph1:digraph.name: digraph
graph1:digraph.description: This symbol refers to a digraph. It has two arguments. The first is the set of vertices, the second is the set of arrows. Arrows are represented by lists of length two, where a list represents the arrow from the first element to the second.
examples: The two-sided infinite directed path. 1
graph1:digraph.description_normalized: This symbol refers to a digraph. It has two arguments. The first is the set of vertices, the second is the set of arrows. Arrows are represented by lists of length two, where a list represents the arrow from the first element to the second.
examples_normalized: The two-sided infinite directed path. 1

graph1:arrowset.name: arrowset
graph1:arrowset.description: This symbol represents the set of arrows of a directed graph. It takes one argument, the directed graph.
examples: The arrow set of the loop consists of one loop. 1 1 1 1 1
graph1:arrowset.description_normalized: This symbol represents the set of arrows of a directed graph. It takes one argument, the directed graph.
examples_normalized: The arrow set of the loop consists of one loop. 1 1 1 1 1

graph1:source.name: source
graph1:source.description: Given an arrow, this symbol refers to the vertex where the arrow starts. It takes one argument, the arrow.
examples: The arrow [a, b] starts at a.
graph1:source.description_normalized: Given an arrow, this symbol refers to the vertex where the arrow starts. It takes one argument, the arrow.
examples_normalized: The arrow [a, b] starts at a.

graph1:target.name: target
graph1:target.description: Given an arrow, this symbol refers to the vertex the arrow points to. It takes one argument, the arrow.
examples: The arrow [a, b] points to b.
graph1:target.description_normalized: Given an arrow, this symbol refers to the vertex the arrow points to. It takes one argument, the arrow.
examples_normalized: The arrow [a, b] points to b.

polyr:term.name: term
polyr:term.description:
A constructor for monomials, that is products of powers and
          elements of the base ring.
          First argument is from N (the exponent of the variable
          implied by an outer poly_r_rep)
          second argument is a coefficient (from the ground field, or a
          polynomial in lesser variables).
polyr:term.description_normalized:
A constructor for monomials, that is products of powers and
          elements of the base ring.
          First argument is from N (the exponent of the variable
          implied by an outer poly_r_rep)
          second argument is a coefficient (from the ground field, or a
          polynomial in lesser variables).

polyr:poly_r_rep.name: poly_r_rep
polyr:poly_r_rep.description:
A constructor for the representation of polynomials.
         The first argument is the polynomial variable, the rest are
         monomials (in decreasing order of exponent).
examples: The polynomial x^2*y^6 + 3*x^0*y^5 = x^2*y^6 + 3*y^5 may be encoded as: 2 6 1 0 5 3
polyr:poly_r_rep.description_normalized:
A constructor for the representation of polynomials.
         The first argument is the polynomial variable, the rest are
         monomials (in decreasing order of exponent).
examples_normalized: $The polynomial x^2*y^{6} + 3*x^0*y^{5} = x^2*y^{6} + 3*y^5 may be encoded as: 2 6 1 0 5 3$

polyr:polynomial_r.name: polynomial_r
polyr:polynomial_r.description:
The constructor of Recursive Polynomials. The first argument
         is the polynomial ring containing the polynomial and the second
         is a "poly_r_rep".
examples: The polynomial x^2*y^6 + 3*x^0*y^5 = x^2*y^6 + 3*y^5 in the polynomial ring with the integers as the coefficient ring and variables x,y in that order may be encoded as: 2 6 1 0 5 3
polyr:polynomial_r.description_normalized:
The constructor of Recursive Polynomials. The first argument
         is the polynomial ring containing the polynomial and the second
         is a "poly_r_rep".
examples_normalized: $The polynomial x^2*y^{6} + 3*x^0*y^{5} = x^2*y^{6} + 3*y^5 in the polynomial ring with the integers as the coefficient ring and variables x,y in that order may be encoded as: 2 6 1 0 5 3$

polyr:polynomial_ring_r.name: polynomial_ring_r
polyr:polynomial_ring_r.description:
The constructor of a recursive polynomial ring. The first argument
         is a ring (the ring of the coefficients), the rest are the 
         variables (in order).
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0" cdbase="http://www.openmath.org/cd"> <ns1:OMA> <ns1:OMS name="polynomial_ring_r" cd="polyr" /> <ns1:OMS name="Z" cd="setname1" /> <ns1:OMV name="x" /> <ns1:OMV name="y" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
polyr:polynomial_ring_r.description_normalized:
The constructor of a recursive polynomial ring. The first argument
         is a ring (the ring of the coefficients), the rest are the 
         variables (in order).
examples_normalized: This symbol represents the natural logarithm function

dimensions1:length.name: length
dimensions1:length.description: This symbol represents the length physical dimension.
dimensions1:length.description_normalized: This symbol represents the length physical dimension.

dimensions1:area.name: area
dimensions1:area.description: This symbol represents the area physical dimension.
cmp_properties: area = length*length
dimensions1:area.description_normalized: This symbol represents the area physical dimension.

dimensions1:volume.name: volume
dimensions1:volume.description: This symbol represents the volume physical dimension.
cmp_properties: volume = length*length*length
dimensions1:volume.description_normalized: This symbol represents the volume physical dimension.

dimensions1:speed.name: speed
dimensions1:speed.description:
This symbol represents the speed physical dimension. It is the size of the
derivative of distance with respect to time.
cmp_properties: speed = length/time
dimensions1:speed.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the speed physical dimension. It is the size of the
derivative of distance with respect to time.

dimensions1:displacement.name: displacement
dimensions1:displacement.description:
This symbol represents the spatial difference between two points.
The direction of the displacement is taken into account as well as the
distance between the points.
dimensions1:displacement.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the spatial difference between two points.
The direction of the displacement is taken into account as well as the
distance between the points.

dimensions1:velocity.name: velocity
dimensions1:velocity.description:
This symbol represents the velocity physical dimension. It is the
derivative of distance with respect to time.
cmp_properties: velocity = displacement/time
speed is the Euclidean norm of velocity
dimensions1:velocity.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the velocity physical dimension. It is the
derivative of distance with respect to time.

dimensions1:acceleration.name: acceleration
dimensions1:acceleration.description:
This symbol represents the acceleration physical dimension. It is the
second derivative of distance with respect to time.
cmp_properties: acceleration = displacement/(time^2)
dimensions1:acceleration.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the acceleration physical dimension. It is the
second derivative of distance with respect to time.

dimensions1:time.name: time
dimensions1:time.description:
This symbol represents the time physical dimension.
Note that the main units for time are defined in the units_time1 CD.
dimensions1:time.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the time physical dimension.
Note that the main units for time are defined in the units_time1 CD.

dimensions1:mass.name: mass
dimensions1:mass.description: This symbol represents the mass physical dimension.
dimensions1:mass.description_normalized: This symbol represents the mass physical dimension.

dimensions1:force.name: force
dimensions1:force.description: This symbol represents the force physical dimension.
cmp_properties: force = mass*length/time^2
dimensions1:force.description_normalized: This symbol represents the force physical dimension.

dimensions1:temperature.name: temperature
dimensions1:temperature.description: This symbol represents the temperature physical dimension.
dimensions1:temperature.description_normalized: This symbol represents the temperature physical dimension.

dimensions1:pressure.name: pressure
dimensions1:pressure.description: This symbol represents the pressure physical dimension.
cmp_properties: pressure = force/area
dimensions1:pressure.description_normalized: This symbol represents the pressure physical dimension.

dimensions1:charge.name: charge
dimensions1:charge.description: This symbol represents the charge physical dimension.
cmp_properties: charge = current/voltage
dimensions1:charge.description_normalized: This symbol represents the charge physical dimension.

dimensions1:current.name: current
dimensions1:current.description: This symbol represents the current physical dimension.
cmp_properties: current = voltage*charge
dimensions1:current.description_normalized: This symbol represents the current physical dimension.

dimensions1:voltage.name: voltage
dimensions1:voltage.description: This symbol represents the voltage physical dimension.
cmp_properties: voltage = current/charge
dimensions1:voltage.description_normalized: This symbol represents the voltage physical dimension.

dimensions1:resistance.name: resistance
dimensions1:resistance.description:
This symbol represents the resistance physical dimension, it is the
resistance that an electrical circuit has to flow of charge.
cmp_properties: resistance = voltage/current
dimensions1:resistance.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the resistance physical dimension, it is the
resistance that an electrical circuit has to flow of charge.

dimensions1:density.name: density
dimensions1:density.description:
This symbol represents the density physical dimension, it is the mass
per unit volume.
cmp_properties: density = mass/volume
dimensions1:density.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the density physical dimension, it is the mass
per unit volume.

dimensions1:energy.name: energy
dimensions1:energy.description: This symbol represents the energy physical dimension.
cmp_properties: energy = mass*length^2/time^2
energy = force*length
dimensions1:energy.description_normalized: This symbol represents the energy physical dimension.

dimensions1:concentration.name: concentration
dimensions1:concentration.description:
This symbol represents the concentration physical dimension, it is the
amount of a substance in a volume.
cmp_properties: concentration = mass/length^3
dimensions1:concentration.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the concentration physical dimension, it is the
amount of a substance in a volume.

dimensions1:momentum.name: momentum
dimensions1:momentum.description:
This symbol represents the momentum physical dimension, it is mass
times velocity.
cmp_properties: momentum = mass*velocity
dimensions1:momentum.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the momentum physical dimension, it is mass
times velocity.
cmp_properties_normalized: $e m m m n o t u = e a c i l m o s s t v y$

dimensions1:power.name: power
dimensions1:power.description:
This symbol represents the power physical dimension, it is energy
per time.
cmp_properties: power = energy/time
dimensions1:power.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the power physical dimension, it is energy
per time.

polyd1:DMP.name: DMP
polyd1:DMP.description:
The constructor of DMPs. The first argument is the polynomial
         ring containing the polynomial and the second is a "SDMP". 
         Should be of the form DMP(poly_ring_d(...), SDMP(...))
polyd1:DMP.description_normalized:
The constructor of DMPs. The first argument is the polynomial
         ring containing the polynomial and the second is a "SDMP". 
         Should be of the form DMP(poly_ring_d(...), SDMP(...))

polyd1:ambient_ring.name: ambient_ring
polyd1:ambient_ring.description:
This is a unary function, whose argument should be a DMP f. When
       applied to  f, it represents the first argument of f, that is,
      ring of the form poly_ring_d(...) used to define f.
polyd1:ambient_ring.description_normalized:
This is a unary function, whose argument should be a DMP f. When
       applied to  f, it represents the first argument of f, that is,
      ring of the form poly_ring_d(...) used to define f.

polyd1:rank.name: rank
polyd1:rank.description:
This is a unary function, whose argument can be a DMP, a poly_ring_d,
       or a poly_ring_d_named. When
       applied to  its argument, it represents the number of variables of the
      polynomial ring involved.
polyd1:rank.description_normalized:
This is a unary function, whose argument can be a DMP, a poly_ring_d,
       or a poly_ring_d_named. When
       applied to  its argument, it represents the number of variables of the
      polynomial ring involved.

polyd1:variables.name: variables
polyd1:variables.description:
This is a unary function, whose argument is a poly_ring_d_named. When
       applied to  its argument, it represents the list of variables of the
      polynomial ring.
polyd1:variables.description_normalized:
This is a unary function, whose argument is a poly_ring_d_named. When
       applied to  its argument, it represents the list of variables of the
      polynomial ring.

polyd1:DMPL.name: DMPL
polyd1:DMPL.description:
The constructor for lists of multivariate polynomial members of the 
         same polynomial ring. The first argument is a polynomial ring
         and the rest are "SDMP"s. DMPL can be attributed with the "ordering" 
         symbol to indicate a particular ordering for monomials of all its
         polynomials. 
         Should be of the form DMPL(poly_ring_d(...), SDMP(...)+)
polyd1:DMPL.description_normalized:
The constructor for lists of multivariate polynomial members of the 
         same polynomial ring. The first argument is a polynomial ring
         and the rest are "SDMP"s. DMPL can be attributed with the "ordering" 
         symbol to indicate a particular ordering for monomials of all its
         polynomials. 
         Should be of the form DMPL(poly_ring_d(...), SDMP(...)+)

polyd1:SDMP.name: SDMP
polyd1:SDMP.description:
The constructor for multivariate polynomials without
         any indication of variables or domain for the coefficients.
	 Its arguments are just "monomial"s. No monomials should differ only by
         the coefficient (i.e it is not permitted to have both "2*x*y" and
         "x*y" as monomials in a SDMP). SDMP can be attributed with 
         the "ordering" symbol to indicate a particular ordering of its
         monomials. This attribute shall not be set if the SDMP is part of 
         DMPL that has this attribute set.
polyd1:SDMP.description_normalized:
The constructor for multivariate polynomials without
         any indication of variables or domain for the coefficients.
	 Its arguments are just "monomial"s. No monomials should differ only by
         the coefficient (i.e it is not permitted to have both "2*x*y" and
         "x*y" as monomials in a SDMP). SDMP can be attributed with 
         the "ordering" symbol to indicate a particular ordering of its
         monomials. This attribute shall not be set if the SDMP is part of 
         DMPL that has this attribute set.

polyd1:term.name: term
polyd1:term.description:
The constructor of monomials. Valid applications are of the form
         Term(coeff, exp1, exp2, ... expn)
	 which represents the monomial 
         coeff * var1^exp1*...varn^expn
         where n is the number of variables, expi are non-negative integers.
polyd1:term.description_normalized:
The constructor of monomials. Valid applications are of the form
         Term(coeff, exp1, exp2, ... expn)
	 which represents the monomial 
         coeff * var1^exp1*...varn^expn
         where n is the number of variables, expi are non-negative integers.

polyd1:poly_ring_d.name: poly_ring_d
polyd1:poly_ring_d.description:
The constructor of polynomial ring. The first argument is a ring
         (the ring of the coefficients), the second is the number 
         of variables as an integer.
examples: The ring of polynomials over the rationals in two variables. 2
polyd1:poly_ring_d.description_normalized:
The constructor of polynomial ring. The first argument is a ring
         (the ring of the coefficients), the second is the number 
         of variables as an integer.
examples_normalized: The ring of polynomials over the rationals in two variables. 2

polyd1:poly_ring_d_named.name: poly_ring_d_named
polyd1:poly_ring_d_named.description:
The constructor of polynomial ring. The first argument is a ring
         (the ring of the coefficients), the remaining arguments are the 
         names of the variables. The first variable given is the most
         important from the point of view of lexicographic ordering, then
         the second, and so on.
examples: By Use of the expression symbol from the CD ring1, an arithmetic expression can be interpreted as a member of poly_ring_d_named. For instance, 2 represents the object 2 1 2 2 13
polyd1:poly_ring_d_named.description_normalized:
The constructor of polynomial ring. The first argument is a ring
         (the ring of the coefficients), the remaining arguments are the 
         names of the variables. The first variable given is the most
         important from the point of view of lexicographic ordering, then
         the second, and so on.
examples_normalized: By Use of the expression symbol from the CD ring1, an arithmetic expression can be interpreted as a member of poly_ring_d_named. For instance, 2 represents the object 2 1 2 2 13

polyd1:anonymous.name: anonymous
polyd1:anonymous.description: Indicates a variable that we do not want to name
polyd1:anonymous.description_normalized: Indicates a variable that we do not want to name

polyd1:plus.name: plus
polyd1:plus.description:
The sum. The argument is a DMPL. The sum lies within the same
         "poly_ring_d", i.e., a program implementing this operation
         should return a DMP with the same "poly_ring_d".
polyd1:plus.description_normalized:
The sum. The argument is a DMPL. The sum lies within the same
         "poly_ring_d", i.e., a program implementing this operation
         should return a DMP with the same "poly_ring_d".

polyd1:minus.name: minus
polyd1:minus.description:
The sum. The argument is a DMPL. The sum lies within the same
         "poly_ring_d", i.e., a program implementing this operation
         should return a DMP with the same "poly_ring_d".
polyd1:minus.description_normalized:
The sum. The argument is a DMPL. The sum lies within the same

polyd1:times.name: times
polyd1:times.description:
The product. The argument is a DMPL. The product lies within the same
         "poly_ring_d", i.e., a program implementing this operation
         should return a DMP with the same "poly_ring_d".
polyd1:times.description_normalized:
The product. The argument is a DMPL. The product lies within the same
         "poly_ring_d", i.e., a program implementing this operation
         should return a DMP with the same "poly_ring_d".

polyd1:power.name: power
polyd1:power.description:
The power. First argument is a DMP, second
          argument is the integer power. The power lies within the same
          "poly_ring_d",  i.e., a program implementing this operation 
          should return a DMP with the same "poly_ring_d".
polyd1:power.description_normalized:
The power. First argument is a DMP, second
          argument is the integer power. The power lies within the same
          "poly_ring_d",  i.e., a program implementing this operation

field1:field.name: field
field1:field.description:
This symbol is a constructor for fields. It takes seven arguments
R, a, o, n, m, e, i: which are, respectively,
a set R to specify the elements in the field, 
a binary operation a on R, an element o of R, and a unary
operation n on R such that [R,a,o,n] is a commutative group, a
binary operation m on R, an element e of R, and a map from R - {o}
to itself such that
[R,m,e] is a monoid and such that [R - {o},m',e,i]
is a group, where m' is the restriction of m to R -{o}.
examples: This example represents the field of rational numbers. The field addition is binary addition, the field multiplication is binary multiplication. 0 1 1
field1:field.description_normalized:
This symbol is a constructor for fields. It takes seven arguments
R, a, o, n, m, e, i: which are, respectively,
a set R to specify the elements in the field, 
a binary operation a on R, an element o of R, and a unary
operation n on R such that [R,a,o,n] is a commutative group, a
binary operation m on R, an element e of R, and a map from R - {o}
to itself such that
[R,m,e] is a monoid and such that [R - {o},m',e,i]
is a group, where m' is the restriction of m to R -{o}.
examples_normalized: This example represents the field of rational numbers. The field addition is binary addition, the field multiplication is binary multiplication. 0 1 1

field1:carrier.name: carrier
field1:carrier.description:
This symbol represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field S (for instance constructed by field).
When applied to S, its value should be the set of elements of S.
examples: The carrier of field(R,+,0,-,*,1,inv) is R.
field1:carrier.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field S (for instance constructed by field).
When applied to S, its value should be the set of elements of S.
examples_normalized: The carrier of the field $(\mathbb{R}, +, 0, -, \cdot, 1, \text{inv})$ is $\mathbb{R}$.

field1:multiplication.name: multiplication
field1:multiplication.description:
This symbol represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field S.    It returns the multiplication map on the field.
We allow for the map to be n-ary.
examples: The multiplication of field(R,+,0,-,*,1,inv) is *.
field1:multiplication.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field S.    It returns the multiplication map on the field.
We allow for the map to be n-ary.
examples_normalized: The multiplication in the field $(\mathbb{R}, +, 0, -, \cdot, 1, \text{inv})$ is $\cdot$.

field1:minus.name: minus
field1:minus.description:
This symbol represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field S.  It returns the map sending an element of S to its additive inverse.
examples: The minus of field(R,+,0,-,*,1,inv) is -.
field1:minus.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field S.  It returns the map sending an element of S to its additive inverse.
examples_normalized: The minus of the field $(\mathbb{R}, +, 0, -, \cdot, 1, \text{inv})$ is $-$.

field1:inverse.name: inverse
field1:inverse.description:
This symbol represents a unary function, whose argument should be a field S.
It returns the map sending a nonzero element of S to its multiplicative
inverse.
examples: The inverse of field(R,+,0,-,*,1,inv) is inv.
field1:inverse.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a unary function, whose argument should be a field S.
It returns the map sending a nonzero element of S to its multiplicative
inverse.
examples_normalized: The inverse of the field $(\mathbb{R}, +, 0, -, \cdot, 1, \text{inv})$ is $\text{inv}$.

field1:identity.name: identity
field1:identity.description:
This symbols represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field.  It returns the identity element of the field.
examples: The identity field(R,+,0,-,*,1,inv) is 1.
field1:identity.description_normalized:
This symbols represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field.  It returns the identity element of the field.
examples_normalized: The identity element for addition in the field \(\mathbb{R}\) is \(0\).

field1:zero.name: zero
field1:zero.description:
This symbols represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field.  It returns the zero element of the field.
examples: The identity field(R,+,0,-,*,1,inv) is 0.
field1:zero.description_normalized:
This symbols represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field.  It returns the zero element of the field.
examples_normalized: The identity element for addition in the field \(\mathbb{R}\) is \(0\).

field1:addition.name: addition
field1:addition.description:
This symbols represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field.    It returns the addition map on the field.
We allow for the map to be n-ary.
examples: The identity field(R,+,0,-,*,1,inv) is +.
field1:addition.description_normalized:
This symbols represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field.    It returns the addition map on the field.
We allow for the map to be n-ary.
examples_normalized: The identity element for addition in the field \(\mathbb{R}\) is \(0\).

field1:subtraction.name: subtraction
field1:subtraction.description:
This symbols represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field.  It returns the binary operation of subtraction on the field.
examples: The subtraction of field(R,+,0,-,*,1,inv) is the map sending the pair (r,s) of elements of R to r-s.
field1:subtraction.description_normalized:
This symbols represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
field.  It returns the binary operation of subtraction on the field.
examples_normalized: The subtraction of the field $(\mathbb{R}, +, 0, -, \cdot, 1, \text{inv})$ is the map sending the pair $(r, s)$ of elements of $\mathbb{R}$ to $r - s$.

field1:is_commutative.name: is_commutative
field1:is_commutative.description:
The unary boolean function whose value is true iff the argument is a
commutative field.
cmp_properties: If is_commutative(G) then for all a,b in carrier(G) a*b = b*a
field1:is_commutative.description_normalized:
The unary boolean function whose value is true iff the argument is a
commutative field.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\text{is\_commutative}(G) \Rightarrow \forall a, b \in \text{carrier}(G): a \cdot b = b \cdot a$

field1:is_subfield.name: is_subfield
field1:is_subfield.description:
The binary boolean function whose value is true iff the second
argument is a subfield of the second.
cmp_properties: If is_subfield(G,H) then H is a nonempty set of elements of the carrier of G and H is closed under multiplication and taking inverses.
field1:is_subfield.description_normalized:
The binary boolean function whose value is true iff the second
argument is a subfield of the second.
cmp_properties_normalized: If $H$ is a subfield of $G$, then $H$ is a nonempty set of elements of the carrier of $G$ and $H$ is closed under multiplication and taking inverses.

field1:additive_group.name: additive_group
field1:additive_group.description:
This symbol is a unary function, whose argument should be a field S.
When applied to S its value is the monoid underlying S.

field1:multiplicative_group.name: multiplicative_group
field1:multiplicative_group.description:
This symbol is a unary function, whose argument should be a field S.
When applied to S its value is the multiplicative group on the nonzero
elements of S.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="relation1" name="eq" /> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="field1" name="multiplicative_group" /> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="field1" name="field" /> <ns1:OMV name="R" /> <ns1:OMV name="plus" /> <ns1:OMV name="zero" /> <ns1:OMV name="minus" /> <ns1:OMV name="times" /> <ns1:OMV name="one" /> <ns1:OMV name="inv" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMA> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="group1" name="group" /> <ns1:OMV name="R" /> <ns1:OMV name="times" /> <ns1:OMV name="one" /> <ns1:OMV name="inv" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
field1:multiplicative_group.description_normalized:
This symbol is a unary function, whose argument should be a field S.
When applied to S its value is the multiplicative group on the nonzero

field1:subfield.name: subfield
field1:subfield.description:
This symbol is a constructor symbol with one or two arguments. The
first argument is a list or set, D, of field elements. The optional
second argument is the field G containing D. It denotes the subfield
of G generated by D.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="field1" name="subfield" /> <ns1:OMV name="D" /> <ns1:OMV name="G" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
This example represents the subfield of the multiplicative field of the nonzero reals generated by the constants Pi and E: 1

first argument is a list or set, D, of field elements. The optional

field1:power.name: power
field1:power.description:
This is a symbol with two or three arguments.  Its first argument
should be an element g of a field and the second argument should be
an integer. The optional third argument is the field G containing g.
It denotes the element g^k in G.
field1:power.description_normalized:
This is a symbol with two or three arguments.  Its first argument
should be an element g of a field and the second argument should be
an integer. The optional third argument is the field G containing g.
It denotes the element g^k in G.
examples_normalized: $3 \cdot 2 \cdot 0 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 9$

field1:expression.name: expression
field1:expression.description:
This symbol is a function with two arguments.  Its first
argument should be a field. The
second should be an arithmetic expression A,
whose operators are
times, plus, minus, unary_minus, and power, and whose leaves are members of the carrier of G. 
When applied to
G and A, it denotes the element (of G) that is the element obtained from the
leaves of A by applying the operations of G instead of those
from the CD arith1 according to A. Here multiplication, addition, subtraction,
minus, and power take over the roles of
times, plus, minus, unary_minus, and power, respectively. 
Also, an integer m occurring in A will be interpreted as a member of G by interpreting it as 
the sum of m copies of the identity element, the symbol alg1.one will be
interpreted as the identity,
and  the symbol alg1.zero will be
interpreted as the zero of G.
field1:expression.description_normalized:
This symbol is a function with two arguments.  Its first
argument should be a field. The
second should be an arithmetic expression A,
whose operators are
times, plus, minus, unary_minus, and power, and whose leaves are members of the carrier of G. 
When applied to
G and A, it denotes the element (of G) that is the element obtained from the
leaves of A by applying the operations of G instead of those
from the CD arith1 according to A. Here multiplication, addition, subtraction,
minus, and power take over the roles of
times, plus, minus, unary_minus, and power, respectively. 
Also, an integer m occurring in A will be interpreted as a member of G by interpreting it as 
the sum of m copies of the identity element, the symbol alg1.one will be
interpreted as the identity,
and  the symbol alg1.zero will be
interpreted as the zero of G.
examples_normalized: $0 \cdot 1 \cdot 63 \cdot 18$

physical_consts1:absolute_zero.name: absolute_zero
physical_consts1:absolute_zero.description:
This symbol represents the absolute zero of temperature, synonymous
with the object of that temperature having zero latent heat.
physical_consts1:absolute_zero.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the absolute zero of temperature, synonymous
with the object of that temperature having zero latent heat.

physical_consts1:zero_Celsius.name: zero_Celsius
physical_consts1:zero_Celsius.description: This symbol represents the zero of the Celsius temperature scale.
physical_consts1:zero_Celsius.description_normalized: This symbol represents the zero of the Celsius temperature scale.

physical_consts1:zero_Fahrenheit.name: zero_Fahrenheit
physical_consts1:zero_Fahrenheit.description: This symbol represents the zero of the Fahrenheit temperature scale.
physical_consts1:zero_Fahrenheit.description_normalized: This symbol represents the zero of the Fahrenheit temperature scale.

physical_consts1:light_year.name: light_year
physical_consts1:light_year.description:
This symbol represents the distant for which a beam of light would
take a year to traverse, in a vacuum.
cmp_properties: one light year is approximately 9221136415095314 metres
physical_consts1:light_year.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the distant for which a beam of light would
take a year to traverse, in a vacuum.
cmp_properties_normalized: one light year is approximately 9221136415095314 metres

physical_consts1:speed_of_light.name: speed_of_light
physical_consts1:speed_of_light.description:
This symbol represents the speed of light in a vacuum. It is
approximately 299792458 metres per second.
cmp_properties: The speed of light is approximately 299792458 metres per second
physical_consts1:speed_of_light.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the speed of light in a vacuum. It is
approximately 299792458 metres per second.
cmp_properties_normalized: The speed of light is approximately 299792458 metres per second

physical_consts1:Planck_constant.name: Planck_constant
physical_consts1:Planck_constant.description:
This symbol represents the fundamental constant equal to the ratio of
the energy of a quantum of energy to its frequency. It is
approximately equal to 6.6260755*10^(-34) +/- 4.0*10^(-40) Joule seconds.
cmp_properties: The Planck constant is 6.6260755*10^(-34) +/- 4.0*10^(-40) Joule seconds this is equivalent to There exists P s.t. 6.626075... -4.0... < P and 6.626075... +4.0... > P and Planck constant = P*Joule*second
physical_consts1:Planck_constant.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the fundamental constant equal to the ratio of
the energy of a quantum of energy to its frequency. It is
approximately equal to 6.6260755*10^(-34) +/- 4.0*10^(-40) Joule seconds.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\frac{The Planck constant is 6.6260755*10^(-34) +}{- 4.0*10^(-40) Joule seconds this is equivalent to There exists P s.t. 6.626075... -4.0... < P and 6.626075... +4.0... > P and Planck constant} = P*Joule*second$

physical_consts1:mole.name: mole
physical_consts1:mole.description: This symbol represents the number of atoms in one gramme of carbon(12).
physical_consts1:mole.description_normalized: This symbol represents the number of atoms in one gramme of carbon(12).

physical_consts1:gravitational_constant.name: gravitational_constant
physical_consts1:gravitational_constant.description:
This symbol represents the constant of proportionality in Newtons law
of universal gravitation which states; Two bodies attract each other
with equal and opposite forces; the magnitude of this force is
proportional to the product of the two masses and is also proportional
to the inverse square of the distance between the centers of mass of
the two bodies. It is approximately equal to: 6.672*10^(-11) Newton
square metres per kilogramme squared.
cmp_properties: The gravitational constant is approximately 6.672*10^(-11) Newton square metres per kilogramme squared
physical_consts1:gravitational_constant.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the constant of proportionality in Newtons law
of universal gravitation which states; Two bodies attract each other
with equal and opposite forces; the magnitude of this force is
proportional to the product of the two masses and is also proportional
to the inverse square of the distance between the centers of mass of
the two bodies. It is approximately equal to: 6.672*10^(-11) Newton
square metres per kilogramme squared.
cmp_properties_normalized: The gravitational constant is approximately $6.672 \times 10^{-11}$ Newton square meters per kilogramme squared.

physical_consts1:Avogadros_constant.name: Avogadros_constant
physical_consts1:Avogadros_constant.description:
This symbol represents the number of atoms in 12 grammes of pure
carbon(12). It is approximately 6.0221367*10^(23) +/- 3.6*10^(17).
physical_consts1:Avogadros_constant.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the number of atoms in 12 grammes of pure
carbon(12). It is approximately 6.0221367*10^(23) +/- 3.6*10^(17).

physical_consts1:Faradays_constant.name: Faradays_constant
physical_consts1:Faradays_constant.description:
This symbol represents the electric charge carried by one mole of
electrons. It is approximately 96485.309 +/- 0.029 Coulombs per mole.
cmp_properties: Faradays constant is 96485.309 +/- 0.029 Coulombs per mole.
physical_consts1:Faradays_constant.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the electric charge carried by one mole of
electrons. It is approximately 96485.309 +/- 0.029 Coulombs per mole.
cmp_properties_normalized: Faraday's constant is $96485.309 \pm 0.029$ Coulombs per mole.

physical_consts1:gas_constant.name: gas_constant
physical_consts1:gas_constant.description:
This symbol represents the constant which is equal to the ratio of the
pressure times the volume and the temperature of an ideal gas. It is
approximately 8.31451 +/- 7.0*10^(-05) Joules per mole per Kelvin.
cmp_properties: The gas constant is 8.31451 +/- 7.0*10^(-05) Joules per mole per Kelvin.
physical_consts1:gas_constant.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the constant which is equal to the ratio of the
pressure times the volume and the temperature of an ideal gas. It is
approximately 8.31451 +/- 7.0*10^(-05) Joules per mole per Kelvin.
cmp_properties_normalized: The gas constant is $8.31451 \pm 7.0 \times 10^{-5}$ Joules per mole per Kelvin.

physical_consts1:Loschmidt_constant.name: Loschmidt_constant
physical_consts1:Loschmidt_constant.description:
This symbol represents the number of particles per unit volume of an
ideal gas at standard temperature and pressure. It is approximately
2.686763 * 10^(25) +/- 2.3 * 10^(20) per metre cubed.
cmp_properties: The Loschmidt constant is 2.686763 * 10^(25) +/- 2.3 * 10^(20) per metre cubed.
physical_consts1:Loschmidt_constant.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the number of particles per unit volume of an
ideal gas at standard temperature and pressure. It is approximately
2.686763 * 10^(25) +/- 2.3 * 10^(20) per metre cubed.
cmp_properties_normalized: The Losch constant is $2.686763 \times 10^{25} \pm 2.3 \times 10^{20}$ per cubic metre.

physical_consts1:magnetic_constant.name: magnetic_constant
physical_consts1:magnetic_constant.description:
This symbol represents the ratio of the magnetic flux density in a
substance to the external field strength for vacuum. It is equal to 
4 pi x 10^(-7) H/m.
cmp_properties: The magnetic constant is equal to 4 pi x 10^(-7) H/m.
physical_consts1:magnetic_constant.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the ratio of the magnetic flux density in a
substance to the external field strength for vacuum. It is equal to 
4 pi x 10^(-7) H/m.
cmp_properties_normalized: The magnetic constant is equal to $4\pi \times 10^{-7}$ H/m.

physical_consts1:Boltzmann_constant.name: Boltzmann_constant
physical_consts1:Boltzmann_constant.description:
A constant which describes the relationship between temperature and kinetic energy for
molecules in an ideal gas. It is approximately 1.380658*10^(-23)
 +/- 1.2*10^(-28) Joules per Kelvin.
cmp_properties: The Boltzmann constant is equal to 1.380658*10^(-23) +/- 1.2*10^(-28) Joules per Kelvin.
physical_consts1:Boltzmann_constant.description_normalized:
A constant which describes the relationship between temperature and kinetic energy for
molecules in an ideal gas. It is approximately 1.380658*10^(-23)
 +/- 1.2*10^(-28) Joules per Kelvin.
cmp_properties_normalized: The Boltzmann constant is equal to $1.380658 \times 10^{-23} \pm 1.2 \times 10^{-28}$ Joules per Kelvin.

setname2:Boolean.name: Boolean
setname2:Boolean.description:
This symbol represents the set of Booleans. That is the truth values,
true and false.
cmp_properties: for all b in the booleans | (there exists an nb in the booleans | nb not= b implies nb = not b)
setname2:Boolean.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the set of Booleans. That is the truth values,
true and false.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\forall b in the booleans \mid (\exists an nb in the booleans \mid nb \neg= b \Rightarrow nb = \neg b)$

setname2:A.name: A
setname2:A.description: This symbol represents the set of algebraic numbers.
cmp_properties: The algebraic numbers are a proper subset of the reals
The rationals are a proper subset of the algebraic numbers
setname2:A.description_normalized: This symbol represents the set of algebraic numbers.

setname2:Zm.name: Zm
setname2:Zm.description:
This symbol represents the set of integers modulo m, where m is not necessarily
a prime. It takes one argument, the integer m.
cmp_properties: for all x in the integers modulo m | there exists an n such that n is an integer and n <= m and x^n = x
examples: The integers mod 12: 12
The integers mod m:
setname2:Zm.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the set of integers modulo m, where m is not necessarily
a prime. It takes one argument, the integer m.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\forall x in the \mathbb{Z} modulo m \mid \exists an n \mid n is an integer \wedge n <= m \wedge x^n = x$
examples_normalized: The integers mod 12: 12
The integers mod m:

setname2:GFp.name: GFp
setname2:GFp.description:
This symbol represents the finite field of integers modulo p, where p is a 
prime.
cmp_properties: x^p = x mod p
setname2:GFp.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the finite field of integers modulo p, where p is a 
prime.

setname2:GFpn.name: GFpn
setname2:GFpn.description: This symbol represents the finite field with p^n elements, where p is a prime.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0" cdbase="http://www.openmath.org/cd"> <ns1:OMA> <ns1:OMS name="eq" cd="relation1" /> <ns1:OMA> <ns1:OMS name="GFp" cd="setname2" /> <ns1:OMV name="p" /> </ns1:OMA> <ns1:OMA> <ns1:OMS name="GFpn" cd="setname2" /> <ns1:OMV name="p" /> <ns1:OMS name="one" cd="alg1" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
setname2:GFpn.description_normalized: This symbol represents the finite field with p^n elements, where p is a prime.
examples_normalized: This symbol represents the natural logarithm function.

setname2:QuotientField.name: QuotientField
setname2:QuotientField.description: This symbol represents the quotient field of any integral domain.
cmp_properties: R is a field iff QuotientField(R)=R
examples: The rationals equals QuotientField(Integers)
setname2:QuotientField.description_normalized: This symbol represents the quotient field of any integral domain.
cmp_properties_normalized: $R is a field iff QuotientField(R) = R$
examples_normalized: $\mathbb{Q} = \text{QuotientField}(\mathbb{Z})$

setname2:H.name: H
setname2:H.description: This  symbol represents the set of quaternions.
cmp_properties: 1 is a quaternion and there exists i,j,k s.t. i,j,k are quaternions and i^2 = j^2 = k^2 = ijk = -1 with abs(i) not = abs(j) not = abs(k) not = 1 implies for all q, q a quaternion implies there exists r_0, r_1, r_2, r_3 reals s.t. q = r_0 + r_1*i + r_2*j + r_3*k
examples: There exists a,b in the quaternions s.t. a*b neq b*a
setname2:H.description_normalized: This  symbol represents the set of quaternions.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\mathbb{H}$ is the set of quaternions; $\exists i, j, k$ with $i^2 = j^2 = k^2 = ijk = -1$; $\forall q \in \mathbb{H}: \exists r_0, r_1, r_2, r_3 \in \mathbb{R}: q = r_0 + r_1 i + r_2 j + r_3 k$
examples_normalized: $\exists a, b \in \mathbb{H} \mid a \cdot b \neq b \cdot a$

mathmlkeys:alternate-representation.name: alternate-representation
mathmlkeys:alternate-representation.description:
This key specifies that the corresponding value is an alternate
    representation of the annotated element in some unspecified way.
examples: An OpenMath expression and one of its alternate representations: the presentation MathML delivered in the context of a spanish speaking user. senx

mathmlkeys:contentequiv.name: contentequiv
mathmlkeys:contentequiv.description:
This key specifies that the corresponding value is the content
      MathML equivalent of the annotated element.
mathmlkeys:contentequiv.description_normalized:
This key specifies that the corresponding value is the content
      MathML equivalent of the annotated element.

list3:length.name: length
list3:length.description:
This symbol represents a function whose argument should be a list.
It returns the length of
its argument.
examples: The length of the list [1,2,3] is 3. 1 2 3 3
list3:length.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a function whose argument should be a list.
It returns the length of
its argument.
examples_normalized: The length of the list [1,2,3] is 3. 1 2 3 3

list3:in.name: in
list3:in.description:
This symbol represents a boolean function with two arguments, an element and a
list. It is used to denote that the element is in the given list.
list3:in.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a boolean function with two arguments, an element and a
list. It is used to denote that the element is in the given list.

list3:list_selector.name: list_selector
list3:list_selector.description:
This symbol takes a positive integer n and a list, and represents the n-th 
 element of that list.
list3:list_selector.description_normalized:
This symbol takes a positive integer n and a list, and represents the n-th 
 element of that list.

list3:select.name: select
list3:select.description:
This symbol takes two lists as arguments, L and M say. The second argument is a
 list containing only entries from [1..n], where n is the length of
L. The symbol represents the 
function which returns a list whose length is equal to the length of
M, and having at position k the  value of L at position M_k.
list3:select.description_normalized:
This symbol takes two lists as arguments, L and M say. The second argument is a
 list containing only entries from [1..n], where n is the length of
L. The symbol represents the 
function which returns a list whose length is equal to the length of
M, and having at position k the  value of L at position M_k.
examples_normalized: $4 \cdot 5 \cdot 6 \cdot 7 \cdot 8 \cdot 9 \cdot 3 \cdot 5 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 6 \cdot 8 \cdot 5 \cdot 5$

list3:append.name: append
list3:append.description:
This symbol represents a function with two arguments, the first of which
should be a list. When applied to A and b, it represents the list
obtained from A by appending the element b to it.
cmp_properties: Appending b to the list constructed from the first element a and the rest lst1 gives the same list as the list constructed from the first element a and the rest the list obtained from appending b to lst1.
Appending b to the list lst increases the length of lst by one.
list3:append.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a function with two arguments, the first of which
should be a list. When applied to A and b, it represents the list
obtained from A by appending the element b to it.
cmp_properties_normalized: Appending b to the list constructed from the first element a and the rest lst1 gives the same list as the list constructed from the first element a and the rest the list obtained from appending b to lst1.
Appending b to the list lst increases the length of lst by one.

list3:concatenate.name: concatenate
list3:concatenate.description: The operation of joining one list to another
cmp_properties: Concatenating b to the list constructed from the first element a and the rest lst1 gives the same list as the list constructed from the first element a and the rest the list obtained from concatenating b to lst1.
The length of the concatenation of the lists A and B is the sum of the lengths of A and of B.
list3:concatenate.description_normalized: The operation of joining one list to another
cmp_properties_normalized: Concatenating b to the list constructed from the first element a and the rest lst1 gives the same list as the list constructed from the first element a and the rest the list obtained from concatenating b to lst1.
The length of the concatenation of the lists A and B is the sum of the lengths of A and of B.

linalg6:matrix_tensor.name: matrix_tensor
linalg6:matrix_tensor.description:
This symbol denotes a n-nary function which is used to construct 
the tensor product matrix of its arguments, which must be matrices.
cmp_properties: If A is an m x r matrix B is an n x s matrix, then their Kronecker product is the m n x rs matrix whose i + (k-1) m, j + (l-1) n entry is A_{i,j} B_{k,l},
linalg6:matrix_tensor.description_normalized:
This symbol denotes a n-nary function which is used to construct 
the tensor product matrix of its arguments, which must be matrices.
cmp_properties_normalized: If \( A \) is an \( m \times r \) matrix and \( B \) is an \( n \times s \) matrix, then their Kronecker product is the \( mn \times rs \) matrix whose \( (i + (k-1)m, j + (l-1)n \) entry is \( A_{i,j} B_{k,l} \).

linalg6:vector_tensor.name: vector_tensor
linalg6:vector_tensor.description:
This symbol denotes a n-nary function which is used to construct 
the tensor product vector of its arguments, which must be vectors.
linalg6:vector_tensor.description_normalized:
This symbol denotes a n-nary function which is used to construct 
the tensor product vector of its arguments, which must be vectors.

ring4:is_maximal_ideal.name: is_maximal_ideal
ring4:is_maximal_ideal.description:
The binary boolean function whose value is true iff the second
argument is a maximal ideal of the first.
ring4:is_maximal_ideal.description_normalized:
The binary boolean function whose value is true iff the second
argument is a maximal ideal of the first.

ring4:is_prime_ideal.name: is_prime_ideal
ring4:is_prime_ideal.description:
The binary boolean function whose value is true iff the second
argument is a prime ideal of the first.
ring4:is_prime_ideal.description_normalized:
The binary boolean function whose value is true iff the second
argument is a prime ideal of the first.

ring4:is_domain.name: is_domain
ring4:is_domain.description:
This symbol represents a boolean 
unary function. The argument is a ring R.
When evaluated on R, the function returns true if R is a domain
and false otherwise. A domain is a commutative ring without zero divisors.
ring4:is_domain.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a boolean 
unary function. The argument is a ring R.
When evaluated on R, the function returns true if R is a domain
and false otherwise. A domain is a commutative ring without zero divisors.

ring4:is_field.name: is_field
ring4:is_field.description:
This is unary boolean function whose argument should be a ring R.
The value is true if and only if the ring is commutative and every nonzero 
element has
a multiplicative
inverse.
cmp_properties: If is_commutative(G) and for all a in carrier(G) there is b in carrier(G) such that a*b = identity(G), then is_field(G).
ring4:is_field.description_normalized:
This is unary boolean function whose argument should be a ring R.
The value is true if and only if the ring is commutative and every nonzero 
element has
a multiplicative
inverse.
cmp_properties_normalized: If \is_commutative(G) and for all \(a\) in \carrier(G) there exists \(b\) in \carrier(G) such that \(a \cdot b = \identity(G)\), then \is_field(G).

ring4:is_zero_divisor.name: is_zero_divisor
ring4:is_zero_divisor.description:
This symbol represents a boolean 
binary function. The first argument is a ring R, the second is an element x of R.
When evaluated on R and x, the function returns true if x a zero divisor and
nonzero in R.
cmp_properties: An element x of a ring R is a zero divisor if and only if it nonzero and there is a nonzero y in R such that x * y = 0 or y * x = 0.
ring4:is_zero_divisor.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a boolean 
binary function. The first argument is a ring R, the second is an element x of R.
When evaluated on R and x, the function returns true if x a zero divisor and
nonzero in R.
cmp_properties_normalized: An element x of a ring R is a zero divisor if and only if it nonzero and there is a nonzero y in R such that x * y = 0 or y * x = 0.

relation0:relation.name: relation
relation0:relation.description: Type constructor; returns the type of binary relations on a set.
cmp_properties: Is defined as "[A:Set] A -> A -> Prop"
relation0:relation.description_normalized: Type constructor; returns the type of binary relations on a set.
cmp_properties_normalized: This symbol is defined as "[A/set] A \to A \to \text{Prop}"

relation0:reflexive.name: reflexive
relation0:reflexive.description: Proposition; the type of reflexive binary relations.
cmp_properties: Defined as [A:symtype][R: (relation A)](x:A)(R x x)
relation0:reflexive.description_normalized: Proposition; the type of reflexive binary relations.

relation0:irreflexive.name: irreflexive
relation0:irreflexive.description: Proposition; the type of irreflexive binary relations.
cmp_properties: Defined as [A:symtype][R: (relation A)](x:A) ~(R x x)
relation0:irreflexive.description_normalized: Proposition; the type of irreflexive binary relations.

relation0:transitive.name: transitive
relation0:transitive.description: Proposition; the type of transitive binary relations.
cmp_properties: Defined as [A:symtype][R: (relation A)](x,y,z:A)(R x y) -> (R y z) -> (R x z)
relation0:transitive.description_normalized: Proposition; the type of transitive binary relations.
cmp_properties_normalized: $(A, R): \text{symmetric relation} \mid (x, y, z \in A) \mid (R x y) \rightarrow (R y z) \rightarrow (R x z)$

relation0:symmetric.name: symmetric
relation0:symmetric.description: Proposition; the type of symmetric binary relations.
cmp_properties: Defined as [A:symtype][R: (relation A)](x,y:A)(R x y) -> (R y x)
relation0:symmetric.description_normalized: Proposition; the type of symmetric binary relations.

relation0:antisymmetric.name: antisymmetric
relation0:antisymmetric.description: Proposition; the type of antisymmetric binary relations.
cmp_properties: Defined as [A:symtype][R: (relation A)](x,y:A)(R x y) -> (R y x) -> (relation1::eq x y)
relation0:antisymmetric.description_normalized: Proposition; the type of antisymmetric binary relations.
cmp_properties_normalized: $[A: \text{symtype}][R: ( relation A )](x, y : A)(R x y) \rightarrow (R y x) \rightarrow (\text{relation1}::\text{eq} x y)$

relation0:partial_equivalence.name: partial_equivalence
relation0:partial_equivalence.description:
Proposition; the type of partial_equivalence relations, 
              namely relations that are symmetric, and transitive.
cmp_properties: Defined as [A:symtype][R: (relation A)] (symmetric R) /\ (transitive R)
relation0:partial_equivalence.description_normalized:
Proposition; the type of partial_equivalence relations, 
              namely relations that are symmetric, and transitive.

relation0:equivalence.name: equivalence
relation0:equivalence.description:
Proposition; the type of equivalence relations, 
              namely relations that are reflexive, symmetric and transitive.
cmp_properties: Defined as [A:symtype][R: (relation A)] (reflexive R) /\ (symmetric R) /\ (transitive R)
relation0:equivalence.description_normalized:
Proposition; the type of equivalence relations, 
              namely relations that are reflexive, symmetric and transitive.

relation0:order.name: order
relation0:order.description:
Proposition; the type of order relations, 
              namely relations that are reflexive, antisymmetric and transitive.
cmp_properties: Defined as [A:symtype][R: (relation A)] (reflexive R) /\ (antisymmetric R) /\ (transitive R)
relation0:order.description_normalized:
Proposition; the type of order relations, 
              namely relations that are reflexive, antisymmetric and transitive.
cmp_properties_normalized: $[A: \text{symmetric relation}][R: (A \times A)] (\forall x \in A, (x, x) \in R) \land (\forall x, y \in A, (x, y) \in R \implies (y, x) \in R) \land (\forall x, y, z \in A, ((x, y) \in R \land (y, z) \in R) \implies (x, z) \in R)$

relation0:strict_order.name: strict_order
relation0:strict_order.description:
Proposition; the type of strict order relations, 
              namely relations that are irreflexive, antisymmetric and transitive.
cmp_properties: Defined as [A:symtype][R: (relation A)] (irreflexive R) /\ (antisymmetric R) /\ (transitive R)
relation0:strict_order.description_normalized:
Proposition; the type of strict order relations, 
              namely relations that are irreflexive, antisymmetric and transitive.
cmp_properties_normalized: $[A: \text{symmetric relation}][R: (A \times A)] (\text{irreflexive } R) \land (\text{ antisymmetric } R) \land (\text{ transitive } R)$

relation0:pre_order.name: pre_order
relation0:pre_order.description:
Proposition; the type of preorder relations, 
              namely relations that are reflexive and transitive.
cmp_properties: Defined as [A:symtype][R: (relation A)] (reflexive R) /\ (transitive R)
relation0:pre_order.description_normalized:
Proposition; the type of preorder relations, 
              namely relations that are reflexive and transitive.
cmp_properties_normalized: Defined as $[A: \text{symmetric relation}][R: (A \times A)] (\forall x \in A, (x, x) \in R) \land (\forall x, y, z \in A, (x, y) \in R \land (y, z) \in R \implies (x, z) \in R)$

indnat:indNat.name: indNat
indnat:indNat.description:
Attribution tag to denote the
    type of inductively defined natural numbers. It is also denoted as
    setname1:N.
indnat:indNat.description_normalized:
Attribution tag to denote the
    type of inductively defined natural numbers. It is also denoted as

indnat:zero.name: zero
indnat:zero.description:

          for the inductive definition of the type of natural numbers
indnat:zero.description_normalized:

indnat:succ.name: succ
indnat:succ.description:
Successor function on the natural number. 
           Constructor for the inductively defined natural numbers. 
           Takes argument a a natural number and returns a natural

indnat:plus.name: plus
indnat:plus.description:
Addition of natural numbers defined recursively
           by using the successor.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0" cdbase="http://www.openmath.org/cd"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS name="eq" cd="relation1" /> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="indnat" name="plus" /> <ns1:OMV name="n" /> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS name="succ" cd="indnat" /> <ns1:OMV name="m" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMA> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS name="succ" cd="indnat" /> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="indnat" name="plus" /> <ns1:OMV name="n" /> <ns1:OMV name="m" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
indnat:plus.description_normalized:
Addition of natural numbers defined recursively
           by using the successor.
examples_normalized: This symbol represents the natural logarithm function.

indnat:times.name: times
indnat:times.description:
Multiplication of natural numbers defined recursively
           by using the successor and plus.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0" cdbase="http://www.openmath.org/cd"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS name="eq" cd="relation1" /> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="indnat" name="times" /> <ns1:OMV name="n" /> <ns1:OMA> <ns1:OMS name="succ" cd="indnat" /> <ns1:OMV name="m" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMA> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="indnat" name="plus" /> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="indnat" name="times" /> <ns1:OMV name="n" /> <ns1:OMV name="m" /> </ns1:OMA> <ns1:OMV name="n" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>

polyd2:ordering.name: ordering
polyd2:ordering.description:
Used as an attribute to indicate an ordering of the monomials in a
          polynomial or list of polynomials. The value of this attribute
          should be one of the constructors specifying ordering.

polyd2:elimination.name: elimination
polyd2:elimination.description:
This is an ordering, which is partially in terms of one
          ordering, and partially in terms of another.
          First argument is a number of variables.
          Second is ordering to apply on the first so many variables.
          Third is an ordering on the rest, to be used to break ties.
polyd2:elimination.description_normalized:
This is an ordering, which is partially in terms of one
          ordering, and partially in terms of another.
          First argument is a number of variables.
          Second is ordering to apply on the first so many variables.
          Third is an ordering on the rest, to be used to break ties.

polyd2:matrix_ordering.name: matrix_ordering
polyd2:matrix_ordering.description:
The argument is a matrix with as many columns as indeterminates
          (= rank). Each row in turm is multiplied by the column vector of
          exponents to produce a weighting for comparison purposes.
polyd2:matrix_ordering.description_normalized:
The argument is a matrix with as many columns as indeterminates
          (= rank). Each row in turm is multiplied by the column vector of
          exponents to produce a weighting for comparison purposes.

polyd2:weighted.name: weighted
polyd2:weighted.description:
The first argument is a list of integers to act as variable weights,
          and the second is an ordering. The result is an ordering.
polyd2:weighted.description_normalized:
The first argument is a list of integers to act as variable weights,
          and the second is an ordering. The result is an ordering.

polyd2:weighted_degree.name: weighted_degree
polyd2:weighted_degree.description:
The total degree of its argument, taking into account any weights 
        declared. The value returned is an integer: non-negative if the 
        weights are. We note that the degree of 0 is undefined.
polyd2:weighted_degree.description_normalized:
The total degree of its argument, taking into account any weights 
        declared. The value returned is an integer: non-negative if the 
        weights are. We note that the degree of 0 is undefined.
examples_normalized: $3 \cdot 1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 1 \cdot 0 \cdot 0 \cdot 1 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 0 \cdot 0 \cdot 3 \cdot 0 \cdot 1 \cdot 0 \cdot 4 \cdot 1 \cdot 0 \cdot 0 \cdot 3$

list3:list_of_lengthn.name: list_of_lengthn
list3:list_of_lengthn.description:
This symbol represents a function with two arguments,
the first of which is a natural number and the second of which is a list.
The first argument is the length of the list.
examples: A list L of length 3: 3
list3:list_of_lengthn.description_normalized:

the first of which is a natural number and the second of which is a list.
The first argument is the length of the list.
examples_normalized: A list L of length 3: 3

list3:entry.name: entry
list3:entry.description:
This symbol represents a binary function whose first argument should be a list
L and whose second argument should be a positive integer i such that
the absolute value of i is in the interval [1..n], where n is the length of L.
If i is positive, it returns the i-th entry L[i] of L, if i is negative it
returns
the (n+1-i)-th entry of L.
examples: The second entry of the list [1,2,3] is 2. 1 2 3 2 2
Specification of the second element of the list [1,..,6] counted from the end. 1 2 3 4 5 6 -2 5
list3:entry.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a binary function whose first argument should be a list
L and whose second argument should be a positive integer i such that
the absolute value of i is in the interval [1..n], where n is the length of L.
If i is positive, it returns the i-th entry L[i] of L, if i is negative it
returns
the (n+1-i)-th entry of L.
examples_normalized: The second entry of the list [1,2,3] is 2. 1 2 3 2 2
The second element of the list [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6] counted from the end is 5.

list3:difference.name: difference
list3:difference.description:
This symbol takes two arguments both a list. It represents a function which returns a list made up of all
the elements of the first list which are not in the second.
examples: Specification of the list [1,..,6], apart from the first 3 elements. 1 2 3 4 5 6 1 2 3 4 5 6

polynomial1:coefficient_ring.name: coefficient_ring
polynomial1:coefficient_ring.description:
This symbol is a unary function whose argument should be a polynomial.
It represents the coefficient ring of the polynomial.
examples: The coefficient ring is often explicitly given as part of the polynomial: 7 1 2 7
polynomial1:coefficient_ring.description_normalized:
This symbol is a unary function whose argument should be a polynomial.
It represents the coefficient ring of the polynomial.
examples_normalized: The coefficient ring is often explicitly given as part of the polynomial: 7 1 2 7

polynomial1:coefficient.name: coefficient
polynomial1:coefficient.description:
This symbol is a binary function whose first argument should be a polynomial
f    and whose second argument should be a non-negative integer n.
It represents the coefficient of the i-th power of the variable in the
    polynomial f.
examples: The coefficient of the first power of X in the polynomial (X+1)^2 in (Z/7Z)[X] is equal to 2. 7 1 2 7 2
polynomial1:coefficient.description_normalized:
This symbol is a binary function whose first argument should be a polynomial
f    and whose second argument should be a non-negative integer n.
It represents the coefficient of the i-th power of the variable in the
    polynomial f.
examples_normalized: The coefficient of the first power of $X$ in the polynomial $(X+1)^2$ in $\mathbb{Z}/7\mathbb{Z}[X]$ is equal to 2.

polynomial1:expand.name: expand
examples: The following expression is equivalent to the arithmetic expression X^2+2X+1 in (Z/7Z)[X]. 7 1 2
examples_normalized: The following expression is equivalent to the arithmetic expression \(X^2 + 2X + 1\) in \((\mathbb{Z}/7\mathbb{Z})[X]\). 7 1 2

polynomial1:degree.name: degree
polynomial1:degree.description:
This symbol represents a
unary function, whose argument should be univariate polynomial.  When applied
to a polynomial, it represents its degree, that is the highest power of the
variable occurring in a term of the polynomial. If the polynomial has no
terms, it is the zero polynomial, in which case the value represented is -1.
polynomial1:degree.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a
unary function, whose argument should be univariate polynomial.  When applied
to a polynomial, it represents its degree, that is the highest power of the
variable occurring in a term of the polynomial. If the polynomial has no
terms, it is the zero polynomial, in which case the value represented is -1.

polynomial1:leading_term.name: leading_term
polynomial1:leading_term.description:
This symbol represents a
unary function, whose argument should be univariate polynomial.  When applied
to a polynomial, it represents its leading term, that is the term  that is the
product of
the highest power of the variable and its coefficient.
If the polynomial is zero, the value represented is zero.
polynomial1:leading_term.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a
unary function, whose argument should be univariate polynomial.  When applied
to a polynomial, it represents its leading term, that is the term  that is the
product of
the highest power of the variable and its coefficient.
If the polynomial is zero, the value represented is zero.

polynomial1:leading_coefficient.name: leading_coefficient
polynomial1:leading_coefficient.description:
This symbol represents a
unary function, whose argument should be univariate polynomial.  When applied
to a polynomial, it represents the coefficient of the monomial of highest degree.
If the polynomial is zero, the value represented is zero.
polynomial1:leading_coefficient.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a
unary function, whose argument should be univariate polynomial.  When applied
to a polynomial, it represents the coefficient of the monomial of highest degree.
If the polynomial is zero, the value represented is zero.

polynomial1:leading_monomial.name: leading_monomial
polynomial1:leading_monomial.description:
This symbol represents a
unary function, whose argument should be a nonzero univariate polynomial.  When applied
to such a polynomial, it represents the highest power of the variable
occurring in the polynomial.
cmp_properties: The leading term of a nonzero polynomial is the product of the leading monomial and the leading coefficient of the polynomial.
polynomial1:leading_monomial.description_normalized:

to such a polynomial, it represents the highest power of the variable
occurring in the polynomial.
cmp_properties_normalized: The leading term of a nonzero polynomial is the product of the leading monomial and the leading coefficient of the polynomial.

units_imperial1:pint.description_normalized:

set2:lift_binary.name: lift_binary
set2:lift_binary.description:
This symbol denotes the lift of a binary operator on elements of X to a 
component-wise operators on subsets of X.
cmp_properties: A lift_binary(op) B = { a op b: a in A and B in B }
set2:lift_binary.description_normalized:
This symbol denotes the lift of a binary operator on elements of X to a 
component-wise operators on subsets of X.
cmp_properties_normalized: $A \cup B = \{ a \cup b : a \in A \text{ and } b \in B \}$

polynomial2:modulo_relation.name: modulo_relation
polynomial2:modulo_relation.description:
This symbol represents a univariate function, whose argument should be a polynomial.
When applied to a polynomial m, it denotes the equivalence relation of being
equal modulo m.
cmp_properties: modulo_relation(m)(a,b) is equivalent to eqmod(a,b,m).
polynomial2:modulo_relation.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a univariate function, whose argument should be a polynomial.
When applied to a polynomial m, it denotes the equivalence relation of being
equal modulo m.

polynomial2:divides.name: divides
polynomial2:divides.description:
This symbol represents a bivariate Boolean function, whose arguments should be
polynomials in the same polynomial ring.
When applied to a and b, it denotes the property that a divides b.
cmp_properties: The polynomial a divides the polynomial b with the same coefficient ring as a if and only there is a polynomial q over this coefficient ring such that a * q = b.
polynomial2:divides.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a bivariate Boolean function, whose arguments should be
polynomials in the same polynomial ring.
When applied to a and b, it denotes the property that a divides b.
cmp_properties_normalized: $The polynomial a divides the polynomial b with the same coefficient ring as a if and only there is a polynomial q over this coefficient ring such that a \cdot q = b.$

polynomial2:eqmod.name: eqmod
polynomial2:eqmod.description:
This symbol represents a Boolean valued trivariate function, whose arguments should be polynomials.
When applied to polynomials a, b, m, it denotes the Boolean 
evalue of the assertion that a and b are equal modulo m.
polynomial2:eqmod.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a Boolean valued trivariate function, whose arguments should be polynomials.
When applied to polynomials a, b, m, it denotes the Boolean 
evalue of the assertion that a and b are equal modulo m.

polynomial2:neqmod.name: neqmod
polynomial2:neqmod.description:

When applied to polynomials a, b, m, it denotes the Boolean 
evalue of the assertion that a and b are not equal modulo m.
polynomial2:neqmod.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a Boolean valued trivariate function, whose arguments should be polynomials.
When applied to polynomials a, b, m, it denotes the Boolean 
evalue of the assertion that a and b are not equal modulo m.

polynomial2:class.name: class
polynomial2:class.description:
This symbol represents a bivariate function, whose arguments should be polynomials.
If a, m are polynomials in a polynomial ring R[X], then class(a,m) denotes the residue class a mod m in
the quotient ring R[X]/ (mR[X]).
polynomial2:class.description_normalized:

If a, m are polynomials in a polynomial ring R[X], then class(a,m) denotes the residue class a mod m in
the quotient ring R[X]/ (mR[X]).

monoid2:is_homomorphism.name: is_homomorphism
monoid2:is_homomorphism.description:
This symbol is a boolean function with three arguments.
The first and arguments are monoids M, N,
the third is a map f from the element set of M to the element set of N.
When applied to M, N, and f, it denotes that f is a monoid homomorphism from M
to N.
cmp_properties: If is_homomorphism(M,N,f) then, for each pair of elements x, y of M, we have f(x * y) = f(x) * f(y).
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="monoid2" name="is_homomorphism" /> <ns1:OMV name="M" /> <ns1:OMV name="N" /> <ns1:OMV name="f" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
monoid2:is_homomorphism.description_normalized:
This symbol is a boolean function with three arguments.
The first and arguments are monoids M, N,
the third is a map f from the element set of M to the element set of N.
When applied to M, N, and f, it denotes that f is a monoid homomorphism from M
to N.
cmp_properties_normalized: $If is_homomorphism(M,N,f) then, for each pair of elements x, y of M, we have f(x \cdot y) = \operatorname{f}(x) \cdot f(y).$
examples_normalized: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="monoid2" name="is_homomorphism" /> <ns1:OMV name="M" /> <ns1:OMV name="N" /> <ns1:OMV name="f" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>

monoid2:is_isomorphism.name: is_isomorphism
monoid2:is_isomorphism.description:
This symbol is a boolean function with three arguments.
The first and arguments are monoids M, N,
the third is a map f from the element set of M to the element set of N.
When applied to M, N, and f, it denotes that f is a monoid isomorphism from M
to N.
This means that f is a homomorphism from M to N,
that f is bijective, and that its inverse  is a homomorphism from N to M.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="monoid2" name="is_isomorphism" /> <ns1:OMV name="M" /> <ns1:OMV name="N" /> <ns1:OMV name="f" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
monoid2:is_isomorphism.description_normalized:
This symbol is a boolean function with three arguments.
The first and arguments are monoids M, N,
the third is a map f from the element set of M to the element set of N.
When applied to M, N, and f, it denotes that f is a monoid isomorphism from M
to N.
This means that f is a homomorphism from M to N,
that f is bijective, and that its inverse  is a homomorphism from N to M.
examples_normalized: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="monoid2" name="is_isomorphism" /> <ns1:OMV name="M" /> <ns1:OMV name="N" /> <ns1:OMV name="f" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>

monoid2:is_endomorphism.name: is_endomorphism
monoid2:is_endomorphism.description:
This symbol is a boolean function with two arguments.
The first argument is a monoid M,
the second is a map f from the element set of M to the element set of M.
When applied to M and f, it denotes that f is a monoid endomorphism from M
to M.
cmp_properties: If is_endomorphism(M,f) then is_homomorphism(M,M,f)
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="monoid2" name="is_endomorphism" /> <ns1:OMV name="M" /> <ns1:OMV name="f" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
monoid2:is_endomorphism.description_normalized:
This symbol is a boolean function with two arguments.
The first argument is a monoid M,
the second is a map f from the element set of M to the element set of M.
When applied to M and f, it denotes that f is a monoid endomorphism from M
to M.
cmp_properties_normalized: If $f$ is an endomorphism of $M$, then $f$ is a homomorphism from $M$ to $M$.
examples_normalized: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="monoid2" name="is_endomorphism" /> <ns1:OMV name="M" /> <ns1:OMV name="f" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>

monoid2:is_automorphism.name: is_automorphism
monoid2:is_automorphism.description:
This symbol is a boolean function with two arguments.
The first is a monoid M,
the second is a map f from the element set of M to the element set of M.
When applied to M and f, it denotes a monoid automorphism f of  M.
cmp_properties: If is_automorphism(M,f) then is_isomorphism(M,M,f)
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="monoid2" name="is_automorphism" /> <ns1:OMV name="M" /> <ns1:OMV name="f" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
monoid2:is_automorphism.description_normalized:
