The first is a monoid M,
the second is a map f from the element set of M to the element set of M.
When applied to M and f, it denotes a monoid automorphism f of  M.
examples_normalized: This symbol represents the natural logarithm function.

monoid2:left_multiplication.name: left_multiplication
monoid2:left_multiplication.description:
This symbol is a function with two arguments, which should be a monoid M
and an element x of M.
When applied to M and x, it denotes left multiplication on M by x.
cmp_properties: left_multiplication(M,x) (y) = x * y.
monoid2:left_multiplication.description_normalized:
This symbol is a function with two arguments, which should be a monoid M
and an element x of M.
When applied to M and x, it denotes left multiplication on M by x.

monoid2:right_multiplication.name: right_multiplication
monoid2:right_multiplication.description:
This symbol is a function with two arguments, which should be a monoid M
and an element x of M.
When applied to M and x, it denotes right multiplication on M by x.
cmp_properties: right_multiplication(M,x) (y) = y * x.
monoid2:right_multiplication.description_normalized:
This symbol is a function with two arguments, which should be a monoid M
and an element x of M.
When applied to M and x, it denotes right multiplication on M by x.

monoid2:isomorphic.name: isomorphic
monoid2:isomorphic.description:
This symbol is a Boolean function with n arguments, n at least 2, which are monoids.
When applied to M_1, ..., M_n, it denotes the fact that there is an
isomorphism from each M_i to each M_j.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="monoid2" name="isomorphic" /> <ns1:OMV name="M" /> <ns1:OMV name="N" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
monoid2:isomorphic.description_normalized:

examples_normalized: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="monoid2" name="isomorphic" /> <ns1:OMV name="M" /> <ns1:OMV name="N" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>

permutation1:endomap.name: endomap
permutation1:endomap.description:
This symbol is an n-ary constructor. Its arguments should
		be positive integers. When applied to arguments a_1,...,a_n,
		the resulting value is the map sending i to a_i for i=1,...,n.
examples: The following expression represents the map on on {1,2,3,4,5} sending 1, 2, and 5 to 2, and 3 and 4 to 1. 2 2 1 1 2
The following expression evaluates to true. 5 1 3 2 4 4 2
permutation1:endomap.description_normalized:
This symbol is an n-ary constructor. Its arguments should
		be positive integers. When applied to arguments a_1,...,a_n,
		the resulting value is the map sending i to a_i for i=1,...,n.
examples_normalized: The following expression represents the map on on {1,2,3,4,5} sending 1, 2, and 5 to 2, and 3 and 4 to 1. 2 2 1 1 2
The following expression evaluates to true. 5 1 3 2 4 4 2

permutation1:list_perm.name: list_perm
permutation1:list_perm.description:
This symbol is an n-ary constructor. Its arguments should
		be distinct positive integers in the interval [1,n]. When applied to arguments a_1,...,a_n,
		the resulting value is the permutation mapping i to a_i for
		i=1,...,n.
examples: The following two expressions represent the same permutation of {1,2,3,4,5}. 2 3 1 5 4 1 2 3 4 5
The following expression evaluates to true. 5 1 3 2 4 4 2
permutation1:list_perm.description_normalized:
This symbol is an n-ary constructor. Its arguments should
		be distinct positive integers in the interval [1,n]. When applied to arguments a_1,...,a_n,
		the resulting value is the permutation mapping i to a_i for
		i=1,...,n.
examples_normalized: The following two expressions represent the same permutation of {1,2,3,4,5}. 2 3 1 5 4 1 2 3 4 5
The following expression evaluates to true. 5 1 3 2 4 4 2

permutation1:is_endomap.name: is_endomap
permutation1:is_endomap.description:
This symbol is an n-ary function. Its arguments should be
		positive integers. When applied to arguments a_1,...,a_n,
		the resulting value is true if a_i is at most n for all i,
		otherwise it is false.
examples: The following expression evaluates to true 1 3 1
The following expression evaluates to false 2 3 5
permutation1:is_endomap.description_normalized:
This symbol is an n-ary function. Its arguments should be
		positive integers. When applied to arguments a_1,...,a_n,
		the resulting value is true if a_i is at most n for all i,
		otherwise it is false.
examples_normalized: $\text{is\_endomap}([1, 3, 1])$ evaluates to $\text{True}$
$\text{is\_endomap}([2, 3, 5])$ evaluates to $\text{False}$

permutation1:is_list_perm.name: is_list_perm
permutation1:is_list_perm.description:
This symbol is an n-ary function. Its arguments should be
		positive integers. When applied to arguments a_1,...,a_n,
		the resulting value is true if a_i is at most n for all i and
		all a_i are distinct, otherwise it is false.
examples: The following expression evaluates to false 1 3 1
The following expression evaluates to false 2 3 5
The following expression evaluates to true 2 3 1
permutation1:is_list_perm.description_normalized:
This symbol is an n-ary function. Its arguments should be
		positive integers. When applied to arguments a_1,...,a_n,
		the resulting value is true if a_i is at most n for all i and
		all a_i are distinct, otherwise it is false.
examples_normalized: $\text{is\_list\_perm}([1, 3, 1])$ evaluates to $\text{False}$
$\text{is\_list\_perm}([2, 3, 5])$ evaluates to $\text{False}$
$\text{is\_list\_perm}([2, 3, 1])$ evaluates to $\text{True}$

permutation1:domain.name: domain
permutation1:domain.description:
This symbol is a function with one argument which is a endomap.  When
applied to a endomap whose arguments are a_1,...,a_n, it represents the
set {1,...,n}.
examples: The following expression represents the set {1,2,3,4,5}. 4 3 5 5 5

permutation1:is_bijective.name: is_bijective
permutation1:is_bijective.description:
This symbol has one argument which should be a endomap p. It returns true
if {a_1,...,a_n}={1,...,n} where a_1,...a_n are the arguments of p and
false otherwise.
examples: The following expression evaluates to true. 1 3 2
The following expression evaluates to false. 2 3 5

permutation1:endomap_left_compose.name: endomap_left_compose
permutation1:endomap_left_compose.description:
This symbol is a binary function. Its arguments should be endomaps with
identical domain D. When applied to arguments P1 and P2, the resulting
value is the endomap which maps x in D to P1(P2(x)).

permutation1:cycle.name: cycle
permutation1:cycle.description:
This symbol is an n-ary constructor.
			It marks a relation on the set of its arguments
				a_1, a_2,...,a_n
			consisting of the pairs (a_i,a_{i+1}) for i=1,...,n-1
			and the pair (a_n,a_1). The arguments a_i should
			all be distinct.
                        The number n is referred to as the length of
 		        the cycle.
examples: The following expression represents the relation on the set {"jan","piet","klaas"} whose members are ("jan","piet"), ("piet","klaas"), and ("klaas","jan"). jan piet klaas
permutation1:cycle.description_normalized:
This symbol is an n-ary constructor.
			It marks a relation on the set of its arguments
				a_1, a_2,...,a_n
			consisting of the pairs (a_i,a_{i+1}) for i=1,...,n-1
			and the pair (a_n,a_1). The arguments a_i should
			all be distinct.
                        The number n is referred to as the length of
 		        the cycle.
cmp_properties_normalized: for i = 1,..., n $\operatorname{cycle}(a_i, a_{i+1},...,a_n,a_1,...,a_{i-1}) = cycle$(a_1, a_2,...,a_n).
examples_normalized: The following expression represents the relation on the set {"jan", "piet", "klaas"} whose members are ("jan", "piet"), ("piet", "klaas"), and ("klaas", "jan"). $\{\text{jan}, \text{piet}, \text{klaas}\}$

permutation1:length.name: length
permutation1:length.description:
This symbol is a function with one argument, which
		must be a cycle. When applied to
		cycle(a_1,a_2,...,a_n), it returns the number n.  This
		number is referred to as the length of the cycle.
examples: The following expression should evaluate to 3. 2 4 3

This symbol is a function with one argument, which
		must be a cycle. When applied to
		cycle(a_1,a_2,...,a_n), it returns the number n.  This
		number is referred to as the length of the cycle.
examples_normalized: The following expression should evaluate to 3. 2 4 3

permutation1:permutation.name: permutation
permutation1:permutation.description:
This symbol is
  an n-ary constructor whose arguments are cycles of length at least 2
  with the property that all entries of all cycles are mutually
  distinct.
	
The permutation symbol constructs a bijective map from the set X of
entries of the cycles to X. The map is defined as follows: if E occurs
as an entry of a cycle, then the permutation maps E to the entry
following E in the same cycle if it exists and to the first entry in
the same cycle otherwise.

When applied to an element y outside X, the constructed permutation is considered to fix y.
cmp_properties: For valid arguments A and B both left_compose and right compose of permutation(A) and permutation(B) are permutations again (that is, evaluate to permutation(C) and permutation(D), respectively, for suitable C and D).
For a valid argument A the inverse of permutation(A) is a permutation again (that is, evaluates to permutation(C) for suitable argument C).
permutation() is the identity.
examples: The permutation (1,5,4)(6,7) sending 1 to 5, 5 to 4, 4 to 1, 6 to 7, 7 to 6, is given by 1 5 4 6 7
permutation1:permutation.description_normalized:
This symbol is
  an n-ary constructor whose arguments are cycles of length at least 2
  with the property that all entries of all cycles are mutually
  distinct.
	
The permutation symbol constructs a bijective map from the set X of
entries of the cycles to X. The map is defined as follows: if E occurs
as an entry of a cycle, then the permutation maps E to the entry
following E in the same cycle if it exists and to the first entry in
the same cycle otherwise.

When applied to an element y outside X, the constructed permutation is considered to fix y.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\forall A, B \mid \text{left_compose}(A, B) \text{ and } \text{right_compose}(A, B) \text{ are permutations again}$
$\forall A \text{ valid} \mid \text{inverse}( \text{permutation}(A)) \text{ is a permutation again}$
examples_normalized: The permutation (1,5,4)(6,7) sending 1 to 5, 5 to 4, 4 to 1, 6 to 7, 7 to 6, is given by \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 5 & 4 & 6 & 7 \\ 5 & 4 & 1 & 7 & 6 \end{pmatrix}

permutation1:is_permutation.name: is_permutation
permutation1:is_permutation.description:
This symbol is a boolean function with
			one argument.  If the argument is not a set of
			cycles of length at least 2, the boolean value
			is false. Otherwise it is true if and only if
			the cycles are disjoint (that is, all entries
			of all cycles in the argument are mutually
			distinct.
cmp_properties: If is_permutation(A) is true then permutation(A) is well defined.
examples: The following value is the boolean false 5 4 4 2 1 whereas the following value is true 5 4 3 2 1

			the cycles are disjoint (that is, all entries
			of all cycles in the argument are mutually
			distinct.
cmp_properties_normalized: If \is_permutation(A) is true then \permutation(A) is well defined.
examples_normalized: The following value is the boolean false 5 4 4 2 1 whereas the following value is true 5 4 3 2 1

permutation1:support.name: support
permutation1:support.description:
This symbol is a function with one argument which is a permutation.
		When applied to a permutation  whose arguments
		are the cycles A1,...,An, it represents
		the set A which is the union of the entries of all Ai
                for i=1,...,n.
examples: The following expression represents the set {jan,piet,klaas,3,4,5}. jan 4 klaas 3 klaas piet 5
permutation1:support.description_normalized:
This symbol is a function with one argument which is a permutation.
		When applied to a permutation  whose arguments
		are the cycles A1,...,An, it represents
		the set A which is the union of the entries of all Ai
                for i=1,...,n.
examples_normalized: The following expression represents the set {jan,piet,klaas,3,4,5}. jan 4 klaas 3 klaas piet 5

permutation1:fix.name: fix
permutation1:fix.description:
This symbol is a function with two arguments. The
		first argument should be a permutation, the second
		argument a set.
		When applied to a permutation g and a set X, it represents
		the subset A of X all points that do not belong to the support of g.
examples: The following expression represents the set {1,2}. jan 4 klaas 3 klaas piet 5 1 5
permutation1:fix.description_normalized:
This symbol is a function with two arguments. The
		first argument should be a permutation, the second
		argument a set.
		When applied to a permutation g and a set X, it represents
		the subset A of X all points that do not belong to the support of g.
examples_normalized: The following expression represents the set {1,2}. jan 4 klaas 3 klaas piet 5 1 5

permutation1:cycles.name: cycles
permutation1:cycles.description:
This symbol has one argument which should be a endomap p. It returns the
list of cycles of p.
examples: The following two objects represent the same list. 2 3 4 2 5 2 3 4
permutation1:cycles.description_normalized:
This symbol has one argument which should be a endomap p. It returns the
list of cycles of p.
examples_normalized: The following two objects represent the same list. 2 3 4 2 5 2 3 4

permutation1:listendomap.name: listendomap
permutation1:listendomap.description:
This symbol is a function with one argument which is a
		permutation whose support consists of positive integers.
		When applied to such a permutation P, it represents
		the list of length n whose i-th entry is the image of i
		under P, where n is the maximum of the support of P.
examples: The following two expressions represent the same list. 1 4 4231
permutation1:listendomap.description_normalized:
This symbol is a function with one argument which is a
		permutation whose support consists of positive integers.
		When applied to such a permutation P, it represents
		the list of length n whose i-th entry is the image of i
		under P, where n is the maximum of the support of P.
examples_normalized: The following two expressions represent the same list. 1 4 4231

permutation1:cycle_type.name: cycle_type
permutation1:cycle_type.description:
This symbol is a function with one argument,
			which is a permutation. 
			When applied to a permutation P,
			it represents the multiset of lengths of cycles 
			occurring as arguments of P.
examples: The cycle type of the permutation (4,3,2,1)(5,6)("jan","piet") equals {4,2,2}: 4 3 2 1 5 6 janpiet 4 2 2
permutation1:cycle_type.description_normalized:
This symbol is a function with one argument,
			which is a permutation. 
			When applied to a permutation P,
			it represents the multiset of lengths of cycles 
			occurring as arguments of P.
examples_normalized: The cycle type of the permutation (4,3,2,1)(5,6)(jan,"piet") equals \{4,2,2\}: 4 3 2 1 5 6 janpiet 4 2 2

permutation1:order.name: order
permutation1:order.description:
This symbol is a function with one argument which should be a
permutation.
When applied to a permutation P, it represents the least positive
integer n for which composition of n copies of P represents the
identity
(that is, a permutation with empty support). 
Note: in this definition of the order, it does not matter whether
left_compose or right_compose is being used.
cmp_properties: The order of a permutation is the least common multiple of the elements of its cycle type.
examples: The order of the permutation (4,3,2,1)(5,6)("jan","piet") equals 4: 4 3 2 1 5 6 janpiet 4
permutation1:order.description_normalized:
This symbol is a function with one argument which should be a
permutation.
When applied to a permutation P, it represents the least positive
integer n for which composition of n copies of P represents the
identity
(that is, a permutation with empty support). 
Note: in this definition of the order, it does not matter whether
left_compose or right_compose is being used.
cmp_properties_normalized: The order of a permutation is the least common multiple of the elements of its cycle type.
examples_normalized: The order of the permutation (4,3,2,1)(5,6)(jan,"piet") equals 4: 4 3 2 1 5 6 janpiet 4

permutation1:are_distinct.name: are_distinct
permutation1:are_distinct.description:
This symbol is an n-ary boolean function.
			When applied to a_1, ..., a_n, it is true if and
			only if the arguments are mutually distinct (that
			is, a_i and a_j are equal only if i=j).
cmp_properties: If are_distinct(a_1,...,a_n) is true then a_1,...,a_n is a valid argument sequence of cycle.
examples: The following expression evaluates to false. 1 3 2 3
permutation1:are_distinct.description_normalized:
This symbol is an n-ary boolean function.
			When applied to a_1, ..., a_n, it is true if and
			only if the arguments are mutually distinct (that
			is, a_i and a_j are equal only if i=j).
cmp_properties_normalized: If \(\text{are\_distinct}(a_1, \ldots, a_n)\) is true, then \(a_1, \ldots, a_n\) is a valid argument sequence of cycle.
examples_normalized: The following expression evaluates to false. 1 3 2 3

permutation1:sign.name: sign
permutation1:sign.description:
This symbol is a function with one argument which should be a
permutation.
When applied to a permutation P, it represents the sign of P,
which is equal to -1 if P is an odd permutation and
equal to 1 otherwise.
cmp_properties: If the cycle type of a permutation P equals [a_1,...,a_m], then the sign is equal to (-1)^(s-m) where s = a_1+...+a_m.
examples: The sign of the permutation (4,3,2,1)(5,6)("jan","piet") equals -1: 4 3 2 1 5 6 janpiet -1
permutation1:sign.description_normalized:
This symbol is a function with one argument which should be a
permutation.
When applied to a permutation P, it represents the sign of P,
which is equal to -1 if P is an odd permutation and
equal to 1 otherwise.
cmp_properties_normalized: If the cycle type of a permutation $P$ equals $[a_1, \ldots, a_m]$, then the sign is equal to $(-1)^{s-m}$ where $s = a_1 + \cdots + a_m$.
examples_normalized: The sign of the permutation \((4,3,2,1)(5,6)\)("jan","piet") equals -1: \(4\ 3\ 2\ 1\ 5\ 6\ \text{jan}\ \text{piet}\ -1\)

permutation1:inverse.name: inverse
permutation1:inverse.description:
This symbol is a unary function. Its
		argument should be a permutation. When applied to
		argument P, the resulting
		value is the inverse permutation of P.
examples: The following two expressions represent the same permutation of {1,2,3,4,5}. 1 3 2 4 5 1 2 3 4 5
permutation1:inverse.description_normalized:
This symbol is a unary function. Its
		argument should be a permutation. When applied to
		argument P, the resulting
		value is the inverse permutation of P.
examples_normalized: The following two expressions represent the same permutation of {1,2,3,4,5}. 1 3 2 4 5 1 2 3 4 5

permutation1:left_compose.name: left_compose
permutation1:left_compose.description:
This symbol is a binary function. Its
		arguments should be permutations. When applied to
		arguments P1 and P2, the resulting
		value is the permutation which maps x in Support(P1)
		union Support(P2) to P1(P2(x)).
examples: Left and right composition of two permutations may lead to distinct results: 1 2 1 2 3 2 3
permutation1:left_compose.description_normalized:
This symbol is a binary function. Its
		arguments should be permutations. When applied to
		arguments P1 and P2, the resulting
		value is the permutation which maps x in Support(P1)
		union Support(P2) to P1(P2(x)).
examples_normalized: Left and right composition of two permutations may lead to distinct results: 1 2 1 2 3 2 3

permutation1:right_compose.name: right_compose
permutation1:right_compose.description:
This symbol is a binary function. Its
		arguments should be permutations. When applied to
		arguments P1 and P2, the resulting
		value is the permutation which maps x in Support(P1)
		union Support(P2) to P2(P1(x)).
examples: Left and right composition of two permutations may lead to distinct results. Compare the following with the corresponding example in the definition of left_compose. 1 2 1 2 3 1 3
permutation1:right_compose.description_normalized:
This symbol is a binary function. Its
		arguments should be permutations. When applied to
		arguments P1 and P2, the resulting
		value is the permutation which maps x in Support(P1)
		union Support(P2) to P2(P1(x)).
examples_normalized: Left and right composition of two permutations may lead to distinct results. Compare the following with the corresponding example in the definition of left_compose. 1 2 1 2 3 1 3

permutation1:action.name: action
permutation1:action.description:
This symbols is
  a binary function whose first argument is a permutation (or a endomap)
  and whose second argument is a point.
	
When applied to permutation or endomap p and point x, it represents the image of
the point x under the permutation p.
examples: The permutation (1,5,4)(6,7) sends 1 to 5, so 1 5 4 6 7 1 5
permutation1:action.description_normalized:
This symbols is
  a binary function whose first argument is a permutation (or a endomap)
  and whose second argument is a point.
	
When applied to permutation or endomap p and point x, it represents the image of
the point x under the permutation p.
examples_normalized: The permutation (1,5,4)(6,7) sends 1 to 5, so 1 5 4 6 7 1 5

permutation1:permutationsn.name: permutationsn
permutation1:permutationsn.description:
This symbol is a unary function. Its argument should
		be a positive integer. When applied to argument n,
		the resulting value is the set of all permutations of the set
                {1,..., n}.
examples: Both sides of the following equality represent the two permutations on {1,2}. 2 12
permutation1:permutationsn.description_normalized:
This symbol is a unary function. Its argument should
		be a positive integer. When applied to argument n,
		the resulting value is the set of all permutations of the set
                {1,..., n}.
examples_normalized: Both sides of the following equality represent the two permutations on {1,2}. 2 12

permgrp:orbit.name: orbit
permgrp:orbit.description:
The binary function whose value is the set of integers which 
are in the orbit of the second argument under the action of the first
argument which is a permutation group.
permgrp:orbit.description_normalized:
The binary function whose value is the set of integers which 
are in the orbit of the second argument under the action of the first
argument which is a permutation group.

permgrp:stabilizer.name: stabilizer
permgrp:stabilizer.description:
The first argument is a permutation group, the second is 
some object (point or set) upon which the first argument acts.
The value is the subgroup of the first argument which 
stabilize the second argument.
permgrp:stabilizer.description_normalized:
The first argument is a permutation group, the second is 
some object (point or set) upon which the first argument acts.
The value is the subgroup of the first argument which 
stabilize the second argument.

permgrp:is_transitive.name: is_transitive
permgrp:is_transitive.description:
The unary function whose value is true iff the permutation group argument acts
transitively.
permgrp:is_transitive.description_normalized:
The unary function whose value is true iff the permutation group argument acts
transitively.

permgrp:is_primitive.name: is_primitive
permgrp:is_primitive.description:
The unary function whose value is true iff its permutation group argument acts
primitively.
permgrp:is_primitive.description_normalized:
The unary function whose value is true iff its permutation group argument acts
primitively.

units_ops1:prefix.name: prefix
units_ops1:prefix.description:
This symbol represents the fact that the subsequent unit has been 
effectively multiplied by 1,000 ($10^{3}$)
cmp_properties: This is unit multiplication by 1,000
units_ops1:prefix.description_normalized:
This symbol represents the fact that the subsequent unit has been 
effectively multiplied by 1,000 ($10^{3}$)

polyd:DMP.name: DMP
polyd:DMP.description:
The constructor of DMPs. The first argument is the polynomial
         ring containing the polynomial and the second is a "SDMP". 
         Should be of the form DMP(PolyRingD(...), SDMP(...))
polyd:DMP.description_normalized:
The constructor of DMPs. The first argument is the polynomial
         ring containing the polynomial and the second is a "SDMP". 
         Should be of the form DMP(PolyRingD(...), SDMP(...))

polyd:DMPL.name: DMPL
polyd:DMPL.description:
The constructor for lists of multivariate polynomial members of the 
         same polynomial ring. The first argument is a polynomial ring
         and the rest are "SDMP"s. DMPL can be attributed with the "ordering" 
         symbol to indicate a particular ordering for monomials of all its
         polynomials. 
         Should be of the form DMPL(PolyRingD(...), SDMP(...)+)
polyd:DMPL.description_normalized:
The constructor for lists of multivariate polynomial members of the 
         same polynomial ring. The first argument is a polynomial ring
         and the rest are "SDMP"s. DMPL can be attributed with the "ordering" 
         symbol to indicate a particular ordering for monomials of all its
         polynomials. 
         Should be of the form DMPL(PolyRingD(...), SDMP(...)+)

polyd:SDMP.name: SDMP
polyd:SDMP.description:
The constructor for multivariate polynomials without
         any indication of variables or domain for the coefficients.
	 Its arguments are just "term"s. No terms should differ only by
         the coefficient (i.e it is not permitted to have both "2*x*y" and
         "x*y" as terms in a SDMP). SDMP can be attributed with 
         the "ordering" symbol to indicate a particular ordering of its
         terms. This attribute shall not be set if the SDMP is part of 
         DMPL that has this attribute set. If the SDMP is ordered, explicitly
         or implicitly via an outer ordering, the terms must be in decreasing
         order with respect to this order. The zero polynomial is represented
         by an SDMP with no terms.
polyd:SDMP.description_normalized:
The constructor for multivariate polynomials without
         any indication of variables or domain for the coefficients.
	 Its arguments are just "term"s. No terms should differ only by
         the coefficient (i.e it is not permitted to have both "2*x*y" and
         "x*y" as terms in a SDMP). SDMP can be attributed with 
         the "ordering" symbol to indicate a particular ordering of its
         terms. This attribute shall not be set if the SDMP is part of 
         DMPL that has this attribute set. If the SDMP is ordered, explicitly
         or implicitly via an outer ordering, the terms must be in decreasing
         order with respect to this order. The zero polynomial is represented
         by an SDMP with no terms.

polyd:term.name: term
polyd:term.description:
The constructor of terms. Valid applications are of the form
         Term(coeff, exp1, exp2, ... expn)
	 which represents the term 
         coeff * var1^exp1*...varn^expn
         where n is the number of variables, expi are non-negative integers.
         coeff should be non-zero.
polyd:term.description_normalized:
The constructor of terms. Valid applications are of the form
         Term(coeff, exp1, exp2, ... expn)
	 which represents the term 
         coeff * var1^exp1*...varn^expn
         where n is the number of variables, expi are non-negative integers.
         coeff should be non-zero.

polyd:poly_ring_d.name: poly_ring_d
polyd:poly_ring_d.description:
The constructor of polynomial ring. The first argument is a ring
         (the ring of the coefficients), the second is the number 
         of variables as an integer.
polyd:poly_ring_d.description_normalized:
The constructor of polynomial ring. The first argument is a ring
         (the ring of the coefficients), the second is the number 
         of variables as an integer.

polyd:poly_ring_d_named.name: poly_ring_d_named
polyd:poly_ring_d_named.description:
The constructor of polynomial ring. The first argument is a ring
         (the ring of the coefficients), the remaining arguments are the 
         names of the variables. The first variable given is the most
         important from the point of view of lexicographic ordering, then
         the second, and so on.
polyd:poly_ring_d_named.description_normalized:
The constructor of polynomial ring. The first argument is a ring
         (the ring of the coefficients), the remaining arguments are the 
         names of the variables. The first variable given is the most
         important from the point of view of lexicographic ordering, then
         the second, and so on.

polyd:anonymous.name: anonymous
polyd:anonymous.description: Indicates a variable that we do not want to name
polyd:anonymous.description_normalized: Indicates a variable that we do not want to name

polyd:ordering.name: ordering
polyd:ordering.description:
Used as an attribute to indicate an ordering of the terms in a
          polynomial or list of polynomials. The value of this attribute
          should be one of the constructors specifying ordering.
polyd:ordering.description_normalized:
Used as an attribute to indicate an ordering of the terms in a
          polynomial or list of polynomials. The value of this attribute
          should be one of the constructors specifying ordering.

polyd:lexicographic.name: lexicographic
polyd:lexicographic.description:
The lexicographic ordering of terms.
          Note that, if a poly_ring_d_named is used, lexigographic refers
          to the order of the variables in the poly_ring_d_named, not to 
          their order as strings.
polyd:lexicographic.description_normalized:
The lexicographic ordering of terms.
          Note that, if a poly_ring_d_named is used, lexigographic refers
          to the order of the variables in the poly_ring_d_named, not to 
          their order as strings.

polyd:reverse_lexicographic.name: reverse_lexicographic
polyd:reverse_lexicographic.description:
The reverse lexicographic ordering of terms.
          Note that, if a poly_ring_d_named is used, lexigographic refers
          to the order of the variables in the poly_ring_d_named, not to 
          their order as strings.
polyd:reverse_lexicographic.description_normalized:
The reverse lexicographic ordering of terms.
          Note that, if a poly_ring_d_named is used, lexigographic refers
          to the order of the variables in the poly_ring_d_named, not to 
          their order as strings.

polyd:graded_lexicographic.name: graded_lexicographic
polyd:graded_lexicographic.description:
Total degree order, graded with the lexicographic ordering.
          Note that, if a poly_ring_d_named is used, lexigographic refers
          to the order of the variables in the poly_ring_d_named, not to 
          their order as strings.
polyd:graded_lexicographic.description_normalized:
Total degree order, graded with the lexicographic ordering.
          Note that, if a poly_ring_d_named is used, lexigographic refers
          to the order of the variables in the poly_ring_d_named, not to 
          their order as strings.

polyd:graded_reverse_lexicographic.name: graded_reverse_lexicographic
polyd:graded_reverse_lexicographic.description:
Total degree order, graded with the reverse lexicographic ordering.
          Note that, if a poly_ring_d_named is used, lexigographic refers
          to the order of the variables in the poly_ring_d_named, not to 
          their order as strings.
polyd:graded_reverse_lexicographic.description_normalized:
Total degree order, graded with the reverse lexicographic ordering.
          Note that, if a poly_ring_d_named is used, lexigographic refers
          to the order of the variables in the poly_ring_d_named, not to 
          their order as strings.

polyd:elimination.name: elimination
polyd:elimination.description:
This is an ordering, which is partially in terms of one
          ordering, and partially in terms of another.
          First argument is a number of variables.
          Second is ordering to apply on the first so many variables.
          Third is an ordering on the rest, to be used to break ties.
polyd:elimination.description_normalized:
This is an ordering, which is partially in terms of one
          ordering, and partially in terms of another.
          First argument is a number of variables.
          Second is ordering to apply on the first so many variables.
          Third is an ordering on the rest, to be used to break ties.

polyd:matrix_ordering.name: matrix_ordering
polyd:matrix_ordering.description:
The argument is a matrix with as many columns as indeterminates
          (= rank). Each row in turm is multiplied by the column vector of
          exponents to produce a weighting for comparison purposes.
polyd:matrix_ordering.description_normalized:
The argument is a matrix with as many columns as indeterminates
          (= rank). Each row in turm is multiplied by the column vector of
          exponents to produce a weighting for comparison purposes.

polyd:weighted.name: weighted
polyd:weighted.description:
The first argument is a list of integers to act as variable weights,
          and the second is an ordering. The result is an ordering.
polyd:weighted.description_normalized:
The first argument is a list of integers to act as variable weights,
          and the second is an ordering. The result is an ordering.

polyd:weighted_degree.name: weighted_degree
polyd:weighted_degree.description:
The total degree of its argument, taking into account any weights 
        declared. The value returned is an integer: non-negative if the 
        weights are. We note that the degree of 0 is undefined.
polyd:weighted_degree.description_normalized:
The total degree of its argument, taking into account any weights 
        declared. The value returned is an integer: non-negative if the 
        weights are. We note that the degree of 0 is undefined.
examples_normalized: $3 \cdot 1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 1 \cdot 0 \cdot 0 \cdot 1 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 0 \cdot 0 \cdot 3 \cdot 0 \cdot 1 \cdot 0 \cdot 4 \cdot 1 \cdot 0 \cdot 0 \cdot 3$

polyd:groebnered.name: groebnered
polyd:groebnered.description:
The constructor for a Groebner basis (reduced, minimal). The first
          argument is an ordering, the second is the Groebner Basis itself
          (with respect to the ordering) that should be represented as a DMPL.
polyd:groebnered.description_normalized:
The constructor for a Groebner basis (reduced, minimal). The first
          argument is an ordering, the second is the Groebner Basis itself
          (with respect to the ordering) that should be represented as a DMPL.

polyd:completely_reduced.name: completely_reduced
polyd:completely_reduced.description:
This attribute, attached to a groebnered object, says 'true' if
          the base is fully reduced, i.e. no monomial is divisible by the
          leading monomial of any other polynomial.
polyd:completely_reduced.description_normalized:
This attribute, attached to a groebnered object, says 'true' if
          the base is fully reduced, i.e. no monomial is divisible by the
          leading monomial of any other polynomial.

polyd:plus.name: plus
polyd:plus.description:
The sum. The argument is a DMPL. The sum lies within the same
         "PolyRingD" i.e. a program implementing this operation
         should return a DMP with the same "poly_ring_d" 
         (or "poly_ring_d_named").
polyd:plus.description_normalized:
The sum. The argument is a DMPL. The sum lies within the same
         "PolyRingD" i.e. a program implementing this operation
         should return a DMP with the same "poly_ring_d" 
         (or "poly_ring_d_named").

polyd:times.name: times
polyd:times.description:
The product. The argument is a DMPL. The product lies within the same
         "PolyRingD" i.e. a program implementing this operation
         should return a DMP with the same "poly_ring_d"
         (or "poly_ring_d_named").
polyd:times.description_normalized:
The product. The argument is a DMPL. The product lies within the same
         "PolyRingD" i.e. a program implementing this operation
         should return a DMP with the same "poly_ring_d"
         (or "poly_ring_d_named").

polyd:power.name: power
polyd:power.description:
The power. First argument is a DMP, second
          argument is the integer power. The power lies within the same
          "PolyRingD"  i.e. a program implementing this operation 
          should return a DMP with the same "poly_ring_d"
          (or "poly_ring_d_named").
polyd:power.description_normalized:
The power. First argument is a DMP, second
          argument is the integer power. The power lies within the same
          "PolyRingD"  i.e. a program implementing this operation 
          should return a DMP with the same "poly_ring_d"
          (or "poly_ring_d_named").

polyd:groebner.name: groebner
polyd:groebner.description:
The groebner basis (lt-reduced, minimal) of a set of polynomials, 
         with respect to a given ordering. First argument is an ordering, the
         second is a list of polynomials. A program that can compute
         the basis is required to return a "groebnered" object.
polyd:groebner.description_normalized:
The groebner basis (lt-reduced, minimal) of a set of polynomials, 
         with respect to a given ordering. First argument is an ordering, the
         second is a list of polynomials. A program that can compute
         the basis is required to return a "groebnered" object.

polyd:reduce.name: reduce
polyd:reduce.description:
The reduction of a polynomial with respect to a Groebner basis. 
         First argument is a DMP, the second argument is a "groebnered" 
         object.
         i.e. a program implementing this operation should return a DMP which
         represents the polynomial reduced with respect to the Groebner basis.
polyd:reduce.description_normalized:
The reduction of a polynomial with respect to a Groebner basis. 
         First argument is a DMP, the second argument is a "groebnered" 
         object.
         i.e. a program implementing this operation should return a DMP which
         represents the polynomial reduced with respect to the Groebner basis.

ring3:is_ideal.name: is_ideal
ring3:is_ideal.description:
The binary boolean function whose value is true if and only if the second
argument is an ideal of the second.
cmp_properties: If is_ideal(S,I) then I is a nonempty set of elements of S and I is a subgroup of the additive group of S and closed under multiplication by elements of S.
ring3:is_ideal.description_normalized:
The binary boolean function whose value is true if and only if the second
argument is an ideal of the second.
cmp_properties_normalized: If \text{is\_ideal}(S, I) then $I$ is a nonempty set of elements of $S$ and $I$ is a subgroup of the additive group of $S$ and closed under multiplication by elements of $S$.

ring3:ideal.name: ideal
ring3:ideal.description:
This symbol represents a
binary function. The first argument is a ring R and the second argument is a
list or a set.  When evaluated on R and such a second argument, the function
represents the ideal in R generated by the entries of the list or set.
examples: The ideal in the free ring on the letters a, b generated by a*b-b*a:
ring3:ideal.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a
binary function. The first argument is a ring R and the second argument is a
list or a set.  When evaluated on R and such a second argument, the function
represents the ideal in R generated by the entries of the list or set.
examples_normalized: The ideal in the free ring on the letters a, b generated by \(a \cdot b - b \cdot a\):

ring3:kernel.name: kernel
ring3:kernel.description:
This symbol represents a
unary function. Its argument is a ring homomorphism f : R -> S.  When evaluated on f, the function
represents the kernel in R of f, that is, the subset {x in R | f(x) = 0}.
cmp_properties: The kernel of a ring homomorphism is an ideal.
ring3:kernel.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a
unary function. Its argument is a ring homomorphism f : R -> S.  When evaluated on f, the function
represents the kernel in R of f, that is, the subset {x in R | f(x) = 0}.
cmp_properties_normalized: The kernel of a ring homomorphism is an ideal.

ring3:principal_ideal.name: principal_ideal
ring3:principal_ideal.description:
This symbol represents a
binary function. The first argument is a ring R and the second argument is an
element of R.  When evaluated on R and such a second argument, the function
represents the ideal in R generated by the second argument.
examples: The ideal in the free ring over the rationals on the letters a, b generated by a*b-b*a:
ring3:principal_ideal.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a
binary function. The first argument is a ring R and the second argument is an
element of R.  When evaluated on R and such a second argument, the function
represents the ideal in R generated by the second argument.
examples_normalized: The ideal in the free ring over the rationals on the letters a, b generated by \(a \cdot b - b \cdot a\):

ring3:free_ring.name: free_ring
ring3:free_ring.description:
This symbol represents a binary function. The first argument should be a ring
and the second a list or a
set.  When evaluated on such arguments R and L, the function represents the
free ring over R generated by the elements (or entries) of L.
This ring can also be viewed as the ring of non-commutative polynomials over R
with variables the elements of L.
examples: The free ring over R on the letters a, b:
ring3:free_ring.description_normalized:

set.  When evaluated on such arguments R and L, the function represents the

This ring can also be viewed as the ring of non-commutative polynomials over R
with variables the elements of L.
examples_normalized: The free ring over R on the letters a, b:

ring3:poly_ring.name: poly_ring
ring3:poly_ring.description:
This symbol represents a binary function. The first argument should be a ring
and the second a variable.  When evaluated on such arguments R and X, the function represents the
free commutative ring over R generated by X.
This ring can also be viewed as the ring of polynomials over R 
with indeterminate X.
examples: The polynomial ring over R with indeterminate X:
ring3:poly_ring.description_normalized:

and the second a variable.  When evaluated on such arguments R and X, the function represents the
free commutative ring over R generated by X.
This ring can also be viewed as the ring of polynomials over R 
with indeterminate X.
examples_normalized: The polynomial ring over R with indeterminate X:

ring3:m_poly_ring.name: m_poly_ring
ring3:m_poly_ring.description:

and the second a list or a
set.  When evaluated on such arguments R and L, the function represents the
free commutative ring over R generated by the elements (or entries) of L.
This ring can also be viewed as the ring of polynomials over R
with variables the elements of L.
examples: The polynomial ring over R with variables a, b:

ring3:matrix_ring.name: matrix_ring
ring3:matrix_ring.description:
This symbol represents a binary function. The first argument is a positive
integer n, the second is a
ring R.  When evaluated on such argument n and R, the function represents the
ring of n x n matrices over R.
cmp_properties: The ring of 1 x 1 matrices over R is isomorphic to R.
ring3:matrix_ring.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a binary function. The first argument is a positive
integer n, the second is a
ring R.  When evaluated on such argument n and R, the function represents the
ring of n x n matrices over R.
cmp_properties_normalized: The ring of 1 x 1 matrices over R is isomorphic to R.

ring3:direct_product.name: direct_product
ring3:direct_product.description:
This is a symbol with two or more arguments, all of which are rings.  
It denotes the ring that is the direct product of its arguments.
ring3:direct_product.description_normalized:
This is a symbol with two or more arguments, all of which are rings.  
It denotes the ring that is the direct product of its arguments.

ring3:direct_power.name: direct_power
ring3:direct_power.description:
This is a symbol with two arguments.
The first argument should be a ring  S
and the second argument a positive integer n.
It denotes the direct product of n copies of S.
ring3:direct_power.description_normalized:
This is a symbol with two arguments.
The first argument should be a ring  S
and the second argument a positive integer n.
It denotes the direct product of n copies of S.
examples_normalized: $0 \cdot 0 \cdot 0 \cdot 2$

ring3:quotient_ring.name: quotient_ring
ring3:quotient_ring.description:
This is a binary function, whose first argument is
a ring R and whose second argument is an ideal I of R.
When applied to R and I,
it denotes the quotient ring of R
by I.
examples: The carrier of the ring of integers modulo 2 is introduced as Zm(2) in the CD setname2. The ring can also be defined as follows. 0 1 0 1 2
The ring (Z/2Z)[x]/(x^2+x+1) 2 2 2 1 Using the xref mechanism it can also be represented as 2 2 1
ring3:quotient_ring.description_normalized:
This is a binary function, whose first argument is
a ring R and whose second argument is an ideal I of R.
When applied to R and I,
it denotes the quotient ring of R
by I.
examples_normalized: The carrier of the ring of integers modulo 2 is introduced as $\mathbb{Z}_2$ in the CD setname2. The ring can also be defined as follows. 0 1 0 1 2
The ring \(\mathbb{Z}/2\mathbb{Z}[x]/(x^2 + x + 1)\) can also be represented as \(2 2 1\) using the xref mechanism.

ring3:multiplicative_group.name: multiplicative_group
ring3:multiplicative_group.description:
This is a unary function, whose argument is
a ring R. When applied to R,
it denotes the group of invertible elements of R with respect to the
multiplication on R.
cmp_properties: The multiplicative group of the ring R is the group of invertible elements of the multiplicative monoid of R.
ring3:multiplicative_group.description_normalized:
This is a unary function, whose argument is
a ring R. When applied to R,
it denotes the group of invertible elements of R with respect to the
multiplication on R.
cmp_properties_normalized: The multiplicative group of the ring R is the group of invertible elements of the multiplicative monoid of R.

ring3:invertibles.name: invertibles
ring3:invertibles.description:
This is a unary function, whose argument is
a ring R. When applied to R,
it denotes the set of invertible elements of R with respect to the
multiplication on R.
cmp_properties: The carrier of the multiplicative group of the ring R is the set of invertible elements of R.
ring3:invertibles.description_normalized:
This is a unary function, whose argument is
a ring R. When applied to R,
it denotes the set of invertible elements of R with respect to the
multiplication on R.
cmp_properties_normalized: The carrier of the multiplicative group of the ring R is the set of invertible elements of R.

ring3:integers.name: integers
ring3:integers.description: This is a symbol representing the ring of integers.
cmp_properties: The ring of integers is (Z, +,0,-,*,1), where +,-,* are the standard arithmetic operations.
ring3:integers.description_normalized: This is a symbol representing the ring of integers.
cmp_properties_normalized: The ring of integers is \(\mathbb{Z}, +, 0, -, * , 1\), where \(+\), \(-\), and \(*\) are the standard arithmetic operations.

magma1:magma.name: magma
magma1:magma.description:
This symbol is a constructor for magmas. It takes two arguments in
the following order: a set to specify the elements in the magma and a
binary operation to specify the magma operation.
The binary operation should act on elements
of the set and return an element of the set.
cmp_properties: A magma is closed under its operation.
examples: This example represents the magma which has as elements all integers, and the magma operation is addition of the square of the first argument to the second. 2
magma1:magma.description_normalized:
This symbol is a constructor for magmas. It takes two arguments in
the following order: a set to specify the elements in the magma and a
binary operation to specify the magma operation.
The binary operation should act on elements
of the set and return an element of the set.
cmp_properties_normalized: A magma is closed under its operation.
examples_normalized: This example represents the magma which has as elements all integers, and the magma operation is addition of the square of the first argument to the second. 2

magma1:carrier.name: carrier
magma1:carrier.description:
This symbol represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
magma G (for instance constructed by magma).
When applied to G, its value should be the set of elements of a magma.
examples: The carrier of magma(G,*) is G.
magma1:carrier.description_normalized:
This symbol represents a unary function, whose argument should be a
magma G (for instance constructed by magma).
When applied to G, its value should be the set of elements of a magma.
examples_normalized: The carrier of a magma $(G, *)$ is $G$.

magma1:multiplication.name: multiplication
magma1:multiplication.description:
This symbol
represents a unary function, whose argument should be a magma G.  It returns
the multiplication map on G. We allow for the map to be n-ary.
examples: The multiplication of magma(G,*) is *.
magma1:multiplication.description_normalized:
This symbol
represents a unary function, whose argument should be a magma G.  It returns
the multiplication map on G. We allow for the map to be n-ary.
examples_normalized: The multiplication of the magma \( (G, *) \) is \( * \).

magma1:is_commutative.name: is_commutative
magma1:is_commutative.description:
The unary boolean function whose value is true iff the argument is a
commutative magma.
cmp_properties: If is_commutative(G) then for all a,b in carrier(G) a*b = b*a
magma1:is_commutative.description_normalized:
The unary boolean function whose value is true iff the argument is a
commutative magma.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\text{is\_commutative}(G) \Rightarrow \forall a, b \in \text{carrier}(G): a \cdot b = b \cdot a$

magma1:is_associative.name: is_associative
magma1:is_associative.description:
The unary boolean function whose value is true iff the argument is an
associative magma.
cmp_properties: If is_associative(G) then for all a,b in carrier(G) (a*b) * c = a*(b*c)
magma1:is_associative.description_normalized:
The unary boolean function whose value is true iff the argument is an
associative magma.
cmp_properties_normalized: $\text{is\_associative}(G) \Rightarrow \forall a, b, c \in \text{carrier}(G): (a \cdot b) \cdot c = a \cdot (b \cdot c)$

magma1:is_submagma.name: is_submagma
magma1:is_submagma.description:
The binary boolean function whose value is true iff the second
argument is a submagma of the first.
cmp_properties: If is_submagma(G,H) then H is a set of elements of G and H is closed under multiplication.
magma1:is_submagma.description_normalized:
The binary boolean function whose value is true iff the second
argument is a submagma of the first.
cmp_properties_normalized: If $H \subseteq G$ and $\forall a, b \in H$, $a \cdot b \in H$, then $H$ is a submagma of $G$.

magma1:is_identity.name: is_identity
magma1:is_identity.description:
This symbols represents a binary boolean function, whose
arguments should be a magma and an element of the element set of the
magma.  When applied to the arguments M and x, it returns true if the
element x is an identity of the magma M, that is, x*y = y* x = y for
all elements y of M.
magma1:is_identity.description_normalized:
This symbols represents a binary boolean function, whose
arguments should be a magma and an element of the element set of the
magma.  When applied to the arguments M and x, it returns true if the
element x is an identity of the magma M, that is, x*y = y* x = y for
all elements y of M.

magma1:submagma.name: submagma
magma1:submagma.description:
This symbol is a constructor symbol with two arguments.
The first argument is a magma M,
the second a list or set, D, of elements of M.
When applied to M and D, it denotes the submagma of M generated by D.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="magma1" name="submagma" /> <ns1:OMV name="M" /> <ns1:OMV name="D" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
This example represents the submagma of the multiplicative magma of the nonzero reals generated by the constants Pi and E:
magma1:submagma.description_normalized:
This symbol is a constructor symbol with two arguments.
The first argument is a magma M,
the second a list or set, D, of elements of M.
When applied to M and D, it denotes the submagma of M generated by D.
examples_normalized: This symbol represents the natural logarithm function.
This example represents the submagma of the multiplicative magma of the nonzero reals generated by the constants Pi and E:

magma1:left_divides.name: left_divides
magma1:left_divides.description:
This symbol is a ternary function.  Its first argument should be a
magma M and the second and third arguments should be elements of M.
When applied to M, a, and b, it denotes the fact that a is a
left_divisor of b in M. This means that there is v in M such that av=b.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="magma1" name="left_divides" /> <ns1:OMV name="M" /><ns1:OMV name="a" /><ns1:OMV name="b" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
magma1:left_divides.description_normalized:
This symbol is a ternary function.  Its first argument should be a
magma M and the second and third arguments should be elements of M.
When applied to M, a, and b, it denotes the fact that a is a
left_divisor of b in M. This means that there is v in M such that av=b.
examples_normalized: $\frac{M}{a} \mid b$

magma1:right_divides.name: right_divides
magma1:right_divides.description:
This symbol is a ternary function.
Its first argument should be a magma M and the second and third
arguments
should be elements of M.
When applied to M, a, and b, it denotes the fact that a is a right_divisor of b in
M. This means that there is v in M such that va = b.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA><ns1:OMS cd="magma1" name="right_divides" /> <ns1:OMV name="M" /> <ns1:OMV name="a" /> <ns1:OMV name="b" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
magma1:right_divides.description_normalized:
This symbol is a ternary function.
Its first argument should be a magma M and the second and third
arguments
should be elements of M.
When applied to M, a, and b, it denotes the fact that a is a right_divisor of b in
M. This means that there is v in M such that va = b.
examples_normalized: $\frac{M}{a} \mid b$

magma1:left_expression.name: left_expression
magma1:left_expression.description:
This symbol is a binary function.
Its first argument should be a magma M, the second argument 
a list L of elements of M.
When applied to M and L, it denotes the left product
(L[1] * ( ... (L[n-1] * L[n]) ... )) of all elements in the list L.
magma1:left_expression.description_normalized:
This symbol is a binary function.
Its first argument should be a magma M, the second argument 
a list L of elements of M.
When applied to M and L, it denotes the left product
(L[1] * ( ... (L[n-1] * L[n]) ... )) of all elements in the list L.
examples_normalized: $32 \cdot 6$

magma1:right_expression.name: right_expression
magma1:right_expression.description:
This symbol is a binary function.
Its first argument should be a magma M, the second argument a list L of elements of M
When applied to M and L, it denotes the right product
(( ... (L[1] * L[2]) *  ... ) * L[n]) of all elements in the list L.

icc:typecoerce.description: Attribution tag to denote type-judgement with coercion

icc:IndType.name: IndType
icc:IndType.description:
Constructor for Inductive Types. 
        Takes arguments the constructor functions for the
        inhabitants of the type and their signatures.
examples: 0 is the defining mathematical property for the symbolic type nat of the inductively defined natural numbers with 0 and succ as constructor functions.

        inhabitants of the type and their signatures.

plangeo2:segment.name: segment
plangeo2:segment.description:
The segment of a line between two points of the line.
The segment is contained in the affine part of the line.
The symbol takes as arguments the two points.
examples: The segment AB:
plangeo2:segment.description_normalized:

plangeo2:halfline.name: halfline
plangeo2:halfline.description:
The halfline starting at A and going through B.
The symbol takes as arguments the points A and B.
examples: <ns0:Example xmlns:ns0="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMathCD" xmlns:ns1="http://www.openmath.org/OpenMath"> <ns1:OMOBJ version="2.0"> <ns1:OMA> <ns1:OMS cd="plangeo2" name="halfline" /> <ns1:OMV name="A" /> <ns1:OMV name="B" /> </ns1:OMA> </ns1:OMOBJ> </ns0:Example>
plangeo2:halfline.description_normalized:
The halfline starting at A and going through B.
The symbol takes as arguments the points A and B.
examples_normalized: This symbol represents the natural logarithm function.

plangeo2:corner.name: corner
plangeo2:corner.description:
The corner between
two halflines L and M, both starting at the same point.  Given three
points A, B and C, the corner A, B, C is the corner of the two
halflines BA and BC.  Corresponding to the two cases, the symbol can
have as arguments two halflines or three points.
examples: or

The corner between

points A, B and C, the corner A, B, C is the corner of the two
halflines BA and BC.  Corresponding to the two cases, the symbol can
have as arguments two halflines or three points.
examples_normalized: or

linalg3:vector.name: vector
linalg3:vector.description:
This symbol represents an n-ary function used to construct (or describe)
vectors.  Vectors in this CD are considered to be column vectors, and must 
therefore be transposed to be considered as row vectors.
examples: An example of vector using n arguments. The specific vector constructed in this example is transpose of [3,6,9]. 3 6 9
linalg3:vector.description_normalized:
This symbol represents an n-ary function used to construct (or describe)
vectors.  Vectors in this CD are considered to be column vectors, and must 
therefore be transposed to be considered as row vectors.
examples_normalized: An example of vector using n arguments. The specific vector constructed in this example is transpose of [3,6,9]. 3 6 9

linalg3:matrixcolumn.name: matrixcolumn
linalg3:matrixcolumn.description:
This symbol is an n-ary constructor used to represent columns of
matrices. Its arguments should be members of a ring.
examples: Representation of a column of a matrix of length two containing the integers [1,0] 1 0
linalg3:matrixcolumn.description_normalized:
This symbol is an n-ary constructor used to represent columns of
matrices. Its arguments should be members of a ring.
examples_normalized: Representation of a column of a matrix of length two containing the integers [1,0] 1 0

linalg3:matrix.name: matrix
linalg3:matrix.description:
This symbol is an n-ary matrix constructor which requires matrixcolumn's
as arguments. It is used to represent matrices.
examples: Representation of a 2x2 identity matrix 1 0 0 1
linalg3:matrix.description_normalized:
This symbol is an n-ary matrix constructor which requires matrixcolumn's
as arguments. It is used to represent matrices.
examples_normalized: A $2 \times 2$ identity matrix: $\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}$

permgp1:group.name: group
permgp1:group.description:
This symbol represents an n-ary function. The first argument is a
group operation 
(usually, left_compose or right_compose),
the other n-1 arguments represent permutations.
When evaluated on such arguments, the function represents the
permutation group generated by the last n-1 arguments.
examples: The permutation group generated by (1,5,4)(2,6) and (1,4,5)(3,6) 154 26 36 145
permgp1:group.description_normalized:
This symbol represents an n-ary function. The first argument is a
group operation 
(usually, left_compose or right_compose),
the other n-1 arguments represent permutations.
When evaluated on such arguments, the function represents the
permutation group generated by the last n-1 arguments.
examples_normalized: The permutation group generated by (1,5,4)(2,6) and (1,4,5)(3,6) is denoted as $\langle (1,5,4)(2,6), (1,4,5)(3,6) \rangle$.

permgp1:support.name: support
permgp1:support.description:
This represents a unary function whose argument should be a
permutation group. When evaluated at a permutation group G, it is the
set of points which are moved a member of G.
examples: The following expression evaluates to the set {1,2,3,4,5,6}. 154 26 36 145
permgp1:support.description_normalized:
This represents a unary function whose argument should be a
permutation group. When evaluated at a permutation group G, it is the
set of points which are moved a member of G.
examples_normalized: The following expression evaluates to the set {1,2,3,4,5,6}. 154 26 36 145

permgp1:generators.name: generators
permgp1:generators.description:
This is a function with one argument, which should be a
permutation group.  When evaluated with argument G it returns the list
of permutations which occur in the definition of G.
examples: The following expression evaluates to the list of permutations [(1,5,4)(2,6),(3,6)(1,4,5)]. 154 26 36 145 2
permgp1:generators.description_normalized:
This is a function with one argument, which should be a
permutation group.  When evaluated with argument G it returns the list
of permutations which occur in the definition of G.
examples_normalized: The following expression evaluates to the list of permutations [(1,5,4)(2,6),(3,6)(1,4,5)]. 154 26 36 145 2

permgp1:orbit.name: orbit
permgp1:orbit.description:
The binary function whose first argument should be a permutation group G.
If the second argument is an element of the support of G,
the value is the orbit of the second argument under the action of G.
Otherwise, it is the singleton consisting of the second argument.
examples: The following expression evaluates to the set {2,3,6}. 154 26 36 145 2
permgp1:orbit.description_normalized:
The binary function whose first argument should be a permutation group G.
If the second argument is an element of the support of G,
the value is the orbit of the second argument under the action of G.

permgp1:stabilizer.name: stabilizer
permgp1:stabilizer.description:
This is an n-ary function with n at least 2.
The first argument is a permutation group G, the other arguments are
elements x_2,x_3,...,x_n upon which G acts. The value is the
subgroup of G consisting of all permutations which stabilize
each of x_2,x_3,...,x_n.
examples: The following expression stands for the stabilizer of 1 and 2 in the permutation group generated by the permutations (1,5,4)(2,6) and (3,6)(1,4,5). 154 26 36 145 1 2
permgp1:stabilizer.description_normalized:
This is an n-ary function with n at least 2.
The first argument is a permutation group G, the other arguments are
elements x_2,x_3,...,x_n upon which G acts. The value is the
subgroup of G consisting of all permutations which stabilize
each of x_2,x_3,...,x_n.
examples_normalized: The following expression stands for the stabilizer of 1 and 2 in the permutation group generated by the permutations (1,5,4)(2,6) and (3,6)(1,4,5). $154 \, 26 \, 36 \, 145 \, 1 \, 2$

permgp1:is_transitive.name: is_transitive
permgp1:is_transitive.description:
This is a Boolean function with one argument, which should be a permutation
group.
When evaluated at a permutation group G, it returns the value true if
and only if the permutation group argument acts transitively
on the support of G.
examples: The following boolean value is false. 154 26 36 145

permgp1:orbits.name: orbits
permgp1:orbits.description:

permgp1:is_primitive.name: is_primitive
permgp1:is_primitive.description:
The unary function with one argument, which should be a permutation group.
Its value is true if and only if G acts
primitively on the support of G. This means that there is no proper subset B
of the support of G with more than one element such that the image of
B under an element of G meets B in a proper nonempty subset of B.

permgp1:schreier_tree.name: schreier_tree
permgp1:schreier_tree.description:
This is a function with two arguments. The first argument should be a
permutation group G, the second argument a point x permuted by G.
When evaluated at G and x, it returns a list of three lists X,V,B.
The first list, X, enumerates the points of the G-orbit of x.
The second list and the third list both have the same length as X, say
n. The second list represents a map
V from  [1,...,n] to {-m,...,-1,0,1,...,m}, where m is the number of
generators of G,
and the third list represents a map B from [1,...,n] to X.
These maps satisfy the following properties:
X(1) = B(1) = x.
Moreover,  V(i) = 0 if and only if i = 1.
For each index i distinct from 1, the value B(i) is equal to X(j) for some index j
smaller than i.
If V(i) is positive, then X(i) is the image of B(i) under the V(i)-th
generator of G.
If V(i) is negative, then B(i) is the image of X(i) under the (-V(i))-th
generator of G.
examples: The following expression represents a Schreier tree. 1543 26 36 1452 4

permgp1:base.name: base
permgp1:base.description:
This is a function with one argument, which should be a permutation group.
When evaluated with argument G it
returns a list of points permuted by G such that the stabilizer of all
elements of the list in G is trivial. Besides, the list is minimal
with respect to the latter property (in the sense that the stabilizer
in G of the elements of no proper
subset is trivial).

permgp1:is_in.description:

should be a permutation, the second a permutation group.

returns true if and only if x belongs to G.

permgp1:stabilizer_chain.name: stabilizer_chain
permgp1:stabilizer_chain.description:
This function takes one argument which should be a permutation group.
When applied to the permutation group G, its value is a list consisting of two lists B, H of equal length.
The first list B is a base for G, whereas the i-th entry H[i] of the
second list is the stabilizer in G of the elements B[1], ..., B[i].
examples: The following expression represents a stabilizer chain. 154 26 36 145
